properties.Name: YWCA Building
properties.ShortDescription: Lincoln's Young Women's Christian Association chapter dates to 1886. In 1906 the chapter commissioned Fiske & Dieman to design a substantial brick home for the association’s social and educational services, on the 15th and N Street site. Less than three decades later in 1932, the YWCA employed Meginnis & Schaumberg (Fiske’s successors) to design the larger replacement building in the Federal Revival style. The south principal facade features rich limestone ornament while the windowless east wall relies entirely on patterned brickwork for enrichment.

properties.Name: LT&T South Telephone Exchange
properties.ShortDescription: The South Exchange was built in two stages, the south part in 1909 and the front in 1920. Lincoln architect Ellery L. Davis was responsible for the Colonial Revival façade with the ornate limestone entry. The building’s location and its rapid expansion both speak to the early evolution of LT&T which was founded in 1903. The building’s original south portion can be best viewed from the alley and features more detailed brickwork on the side walls.

properties.Name: Grainger (Joseph & Alice) House
properties.ShortDescription: When John Fitzgerald built his Lincoln mansion in 1880 he positioned it at the crest of a ten acre parcel bounded by 19th, 20th, A, and D Streets. The mansion was still standing when his widow sold “Mt. Emerald” in 1905 and in the subdivision of the same name Lot 1 was assigned to the mansion. The Grainger House occupies the south half of Lot 1. Built in 1910 by C. A. Schaaf, it was the home of Joseph and Alice Grainger. He was the vice president of J. Grainger Company, wholesale grocers at 8th and O Streets. A fine cast iron fence enclosed the prominent corner lot.

properties.Name: Noble-Dawes House
properties.ShortDescription: Built around 1885 for photographer Henry E. Noble, this Queen Anne style duplex was the home of Charles G. Dawes from 1891-1895. Born in Ohio in 1865, Dawes was a recent graduate from Cincinnati Law School when he was admitted to the Nebraska Bar in 1886. He practiced law in Lincoln for a decade and during that time was part of the circle of brilliant young men including William Jennings Bryan and John J. Pershing who went on to careers of national and international impact. Dawes relocated to Chicago in the mid-1890s where he was a very successful financier. He also served in numerous public offices including US Comptroller of the Currency (1897-1901), US Army Brigadier General during WWI, first US Budget Director in 1921, winner of Nobel Peace Prize in 1924 for reconstruction efforts in Europe after WWI, US Vice President (1925-29), and US Ambassador to Great Britain (1929-32).

properties.Name: German Evangelical Lutheran Immanuel Church
properties.ShortDescription: The German Evangelical Lutheran Immanuel Church and School was designed by Tyler & Brandt and built in 1910 by F. W. Rische to serve a congregation of Germans from Russia. Rev. W. F. Baeder led the church and school, which enrolled as many as 250 students. This is one of the few churches recorded in Nebraska which was a combined church and school facility. The school was often referred to as the “Baeder School.”

properties.Name: A Street Water & Power Station (WaterPark)
properties.ShortDescription: The City of Lincoln constructed this sturdy, Neo-Classical Revival building in 1924 according to plans by Fiske & Meginnis to house municipal utilities, combining water pumping and electric generating facilities. After it became outmoded in the 1970s, it was adapted into 39 residential units in 1987. The WaterPark project designed by Sinclair Hille received a National Preservation Honor Award in 1992 from the National Trust for Historic Preservation.

properties.Name: Scottish Rite Temple
properties.ShortDescription: The Scottish Rite Temple is a reinforced concrete, Neo-Classical Revival style building sheathed in Indiana limestone. The temple's most prominent feature is a colossal order of ten Roman Doric engaged columns on the front facade. When the temple was constructed in 1916, there were seventeen Masonic organizations in the city. The building was an early work of prominent Lincoln architect Ellery L. Davis, who with partner George Berlinghof had designed Lincoln High School of 1913-15. These buildings share similar entries between giant columns opening onto marble staircases.

properties.Name: Terminal Building
properties.ShortDescription: The ten-story Terminal Building was planned in 1915 and erected in 1916 as the headquarters for Lincoln Traction Company. The Lincoln Traction Company, formed in 1897 as a reorganization of the Lincoln Street Railway Company, was the major street railway company in the city until the end of streetcar service in 1945. Architect Paul V. Hyland of Chicago designed the reinforced concrete office building in the Commercial Style with white-glazed terra cotta and bold cornices on the street facades. Hyland’s design contributions to Lincoln also include the First National Bank Building (across the street west from the Terminal Building), the McAfee House at 1801 C Street, and the Frank and Nelle Woods House at 2501 Sheridan.

properties.Name: Lincoln Liberty Life Building
properties.ShortDescription: This structure had its beginnings in 1907-08 as the five-story Little Building, designed by Fiske & Dieman in the early 20th century Commercial Style, topped with a bold cornice. When redesigned in 1936 for the Lincoln Liberty Life Insurance Company by the architectural firm of Meginnis & Schaumberg, the building was reimagined as one of Lincoln’s best Art Deco style office buildings. Decorative limestone was added at the first floor level and cladding the new, windowless sixth floor, replacing the cornice.

properties.Name: Watkins (Albert & Margaret) House
properties.ShortDescription: Architect John H. W. Hawkins designed this Queen Anne style house of 1887 for Albert Watkins, a newspaper publisher, historian (co-author of the Morton-Watkins Illustrated History of Nebraska), and long-time editor for Nebraska State Historical Society. The complex massing and rooflines, ornate trim, and ample use of small panes of colored glass are characteristic Queen Anne features.

properties.Name: Taylor (John & Levina) House
properties.ShortDescription: The John and Levina Taylor House, built around 1890, demonstrates the persistence of the Italianate style among conservative Lincoln builders well after the style’s heyday in the 1860s and ‘70s. The proportions, roof type, window trim, and especially the bracketed cornice are all characteristically Italianate, while the porch is a modification of the early 20th century. John Taylor was a farmer with extensive land holdings between 56th and 70th, south of O Street. Taylor Park and Taylor Meadows carry his name.

properties.Name: Cultra (James & Caroline) Duplex
properties.ShortDescription: Cultra Duplex was built circa 1894 to provide generous-sized homes to two families, and is one of the best surviving multi-family homes from 19th century Lincoln. The single front door opens onto twin staircases, and the houses are symmetrically arranged around a central dividing wall. The builder James A. Cultra and his son George W. Cultra were partners in a coffee, tea, and spice business at 8th and P Streets called Rowan, Cultra, and Co.

properties.Name: Kennard House (Nebraska Statehood Memorial)
properties.ShortDescription: Built in 1869 for Nebraska’s first Secretary of State, the Thomas P. and Livia Kennard House is the oldest residence still standing in the original boundaries of Lincoln. Chicago architect John Keys Winchell designed similar Italianate houses for all three of the original Capital Commissioners – Kennard, State Auditor John Gillespie, and Governor David Butler. Only Kennard’s house is extant. He resided in the house until his wife’s death in 1887 whereupon he built a new house nearby at the corner of 17th and H. In 1965 the Unicameral designated the Kennard House as the "Nebraska Statehood Memorial" and the Nebraska State Historical Society commenced its restoration.

properties.Name: Nebraska State Capitol
properties.ShortDescription: The Nebraska State Capitol, the product of a nationwide design competition won by New York Architect Bertram Grosvenor Goodhue in 1920. The present building, the third to be erected on this site, was the nation’s first statehouse design to radically depart from the prototypical form of the nation’s Capitol and to use an office tower. Constructed in four phases over ten years from 1922-1932, the building, with furnishings and landscaping, was completed at a cost just under $10 million. To fully integrate arts into the building, Bertram Goodhue selected Lee Lawrie, sculptor; Hildreth Meiere, tile and mosaic designer; and Hartley B. Alexander, thematic consultant for inscription and symbolism.

properties.Name: Rock Island Depot
properties.ShortDescription: Chicago, Rock Island & Pacific Railroad was the last major line to enter Lincoln in 1893. They built their passenger depot the same year in the Chateauesque style. Plans for the building were prepared under the direction of Chief Engineer R. W. Day of the Rock Island line. Having discontinued passenger service to Lincoln, the railroad sold this building to City National Bank in 1968. Its renovation into a branch bank by 1969 was a pioneering effort at adaptive reuse and the facility remains a bank in the 21st Century.

properties.Name: Ferguson (William & Myrtle) House
properties.ShortDescription: Entrepreneur William Henry Ferguson built his sturdy Renaissance Revival mansion on Capitol Square in 1909-1911, thirty years after coming to Nebraska in a covered wagon. His early efforts in agriculture, innovating in the planting of winter wheat and alfalfa, led to grain dealing and milling and eventual ownership of eighty grain elevators. He was involved in a multitude of local businesses including Beatrice Creamery Company, Yankee Hill Brick Company, and Capital Beach Amusement Park. His Cleveland architects, Searles, Hirsch & Gavin, introduced several structural innovations to Lincoln house building, including reinforced concrete floors on the lower levels and steel beams supporting the upper floors.

properties.Name: Security Mutual Building (Centerstone)
properties.ShortDescription: In 1887 investors and brothers C. C. and L. C. Burr developed a six-story skyscraper on this site, designed by James Tyler. The “Burrs’ Block” was Lincoln’s tallest office building featuring rough limestone walls, an elevator, bay windows, and an ornate skyline with spires and small domes. By 1916 Lincoln had taller office buildings in the Chicago style, such as First National Bank Building and the Terminal Building, both at 10th and O. Security Mutual Life Insurance Company, then owners of the Burrs’ Block, undertook a unique redevelopment of their property. Berlinghof & Davis reconceived the building as a ten-story structure with the bold cornice and regular window pattern of a Chicago style skyscraper. The complex reconstruction retained some of the existing stone walls but added new interior structure and additional height perfectly matching the original stonework. For over four decades the building housed the Security Mutual Life Insurance Company. It is now known as Centerstone offering commercial and residential space.

properties.Name: Tyler (William & Sarah) House
properties.ShortDescription: English-born architect James Tyler (1844-1919) designed one of Lincoln's finest Queen Anne style houses for his brother William Tyler in 1890-91. William operated a stone company and displayed his wares amply in ornamenting his brick house. According to a newspaper of the time, “Mr. Tyler intends to make the stone work very elaborate in order than it may be an advertisement of his business as well as a thing of beauty and a joy forever." The corner tower with an octagonal, ogee-curved, slate-covered roof is especially noteworthy. T. P. Harrison & Bros. were contractors for the Tylers' project.

properties.Name: Nebraska Telephone Company
properties.ShortDescription: This three-story commercial building in the Renaissance Revival style is the only Lincoln example of the work of Thomas Rogers Kimball of the Omaha architectural firm of Walker & Kimball. Kimball achieved national prominence and directed the highly-successful architectural competition that selected Bertram G. Goodhue to design the Nebraska State Capitol. Constructed in 1894-96 to sustain the loads of the telephone equipment and to provide a modern, fire resistant structure, the building housed Lincoln’s branch of the Bell Telephone system before its acquisition by the locally-owned Lincoln Telephone & Telegraph.

properties.Name: Barr Terrace
properties.ShortDescription: Ferdinand C. Fiske came to Lincoln in 1887 and soon established himself as one of the leading architects in the booming capital city. Barr Terrace, a brick and stone row house of six side-by-side homes, was one of his first major projects; Lincoln's other surviving rowhouse, the nearby Lyman Terrace at 1111-19 H Street, was also designed by Fiske. Although they maintain the rowhouse form, their interiors were reconfigured into numerous apartments by the early 20th century.

properties.Name: Phillips (Rolla & Mary) Castle
properties.ShortDescription: The Phillips House, designed by John H. W. Hawkins and built in 1889-90, is one of Nebraska's finest examples of the Richardsonian Romanesque architectural style. This style is characterized by heavy stone massing, an asymmetrical façade, irregular rooflines that commonly include a tower, and arches springing from heavy piers. All are displayed prominently on the Phillips house. The interior is finished in wood or ceramic tile in various Victorian motifs and includes fifteen fireplaces. R. O. Phillips played a prominent role in the early history and development of Lincoln. A townsite representative for the Burlington & Missouri River Railroad, Phillips was prominently involved with the building up of towns along this line in Nebraska, Kansas, and Colorado. As a lawyer playing an active role in Lincoln politics he served as deputy county clerk, county clerk and as a member of the Nebraska legislature. He was secretary and treasurer of the Lincoln Land Company and headed the South Platte Company.

properties.Name: Maple Lodge (Ziemer House)
properties.ShortDescription: The house, built in 1909-10 for Arthur and Julia Ziemer, is one of Nebraska’s best examples of the Shingle style. Designed by Lincoln architect Ferdinand C. Fiske shortly before he ended his partnership with Charles Dieman of Iowa, the house displays the same material—wood shingles—flowing across the walls, roofs, and dormers. In contrast, Colorado redstone provides a rough texture to the entry porch and decorative accents. Mr. Ziemer was an early resident of Lincoln, arriving in 1870. His varied career included serving as a Burlington Railroad ticket agent, interior designer, and Christian Science healer.

properties.Name: Veith Building
properties.ShortDescription: Veith Building in Haymarket is individually listed on the National Register as the most intact small, 19th century commercial building in Lincoln. Designed by the Lincoln architects Smith & Tyler and built in 1884, it was originally a grocery store with an apartment above. The building features a cast-iron storefront and pressed metal cornice. The cast-iron work bears the trademark of "Seaton and Lea, Atchison Kansas." That firm expanded to Lincoln in 1881 and built a foundry at 8th and Q Streets, which was probably the source of this and other Seaton & Lea ironwork in the district.

properties.Name: State Arsenal
properties.ShortDescription: The State Arsenal, built in 1913 and designed by Omaha architect Burd F. Miller, was the first permanent facility provided by the Nebraska legislature for support of the Nebraska National Guard, successor to the Nebraska Volunteer Militia. The two-story, rectangular, concrete and brick building was used by the Guard as a warehouse until 1963, when it was transferred to the State Fair board and became a military museum. Ownership transferred to UNL when the State Fair moved to Grand Island.

properties.Name: Royer-Williams House
properties.ShortDescription: The Royer-Williams House was constructed in the late 1880s in the Queen Anne style. Henry Royer built and occupied the richly detailed house until 1898 when it was purchased by Dr. Hattie Plum Williams and her husband Thomas. Dr. Williams was a University of Nebraska sociologist whose pioneering work focused on Lincoln’s Germans from Russia. Early in the Williams’ residency the Neo-Classical porch was added to the house, which remained their home until their deaths in the 1960s.

properties.Name: Harris (Sarah) House
properties.ShortDescription: The Harris House was built for Sarah F. Harris, widow of George Harris, who served as a land commissioner for the Burlington and Missouri Railroad. Sarah and George settled in Lincoln in 1872 and he died in 1874. Widow Sarah raised their seven children in their new community. One son became president of CB&QRR, another founded Harris Upham investment bankers in New York City. Her sons provided their mother with this fine Neo-Classical Revival style house in 1901-03 and donated the land that became “Pioneers Park” in honor of Sarah and George in 1928. The City recognized the family’s contributions in the naming of Harris Overpass.

properties.Name: Gold & Company Department Store
properties.ShortDescription: In 1902 William Gold, a native of New York, established "The Peoples' Store," a modest retail business in downtown Lincoln. The firm was incorporated in 1915 with William Gold as president and son Nathan as vice-president and was later renamed "Gold and Company." The building is a landmark in Lincoln's downtown business area. The oldest section at the corner of 11th and O which is six stories high and displays Gothic Revival detailing was designed by Davis & Wilson and erected in 1924. Additions were made in 1929, 1947, and 1951, and illustrate the phenomenal growth experienced by the store. In 1964 Gold and Company merged with Omaha's J. L. Brandeis and Sons, and the business was named "Brandeis, Gold's Division" until 1980 when the store was closed. The building has been rehabilitated for retail and office space.

properties.Name: Hotel Capital (Georgian Place & YMCA)
properties.ShortDescription: Eugene C. Eppley of Omaha owned the Lincoln Hotel at 9th and P Streets when a group of Lincoln businessmen formed the Lancaster Hotel Company and built the community-owned Cornhusker Hotel at 13th and M Streets in 1925-26. Eppley responded by extensively renovating his Lincoln Hotel (built in 1894) and by constructing the Hotel Capital at 11th and P Streets in 1925-26, designed by H. T. Stevens & Company of Chicago. At eleven stories, the red-brick Hotel Capital was one story taller than the new Cornhusker. Its abundant limestone trim in the Colonial or "Georgian" Revival style led to its renaming as "Georgian Place" when it was converted to condominiums in 1983.

properties.Name: Tifereth Israel Synagogue
properties.ShortDescription: Tifereth Israel Synagogue was built in 1912-13 for Lincoln’s Orthodox Jewish congregation. Lincoln architect A. W. Woods, who produced church designs built throughout Lincoln and in two dozen states around the country, was responsible for the simplified Neo-Classical form of this small synagogue. After the congregation built its new synagogue on Sheridan near 33rd Street in the late 1950s their former location served as Lincoln’s Community Playhouse and later as church organ builder Gene Bedient’s workshop. Lincoln architect < target = "_blank" href = "http://www.e-nebraskahistory.org/index.php?title=James_%E2%80%9CJim%E2%80%9D_C._Hille,_Architect">Jim Hille converted the former synagogue to apartments in the mid-1980s.

properties.Name: Calhoun (James & Odus) House
properties.ShortDescription: James D. Calhoun, was a newspaper editor and early supporter of William Jennings Bryan. His large Queen Anne style house was built in 1889-1890 from a design published in 1887 in Shoppell's Modern Houses, demonstrating one of the significant ways in which architectural ideas and fashions were popularized.

properties.Name: Ryons-Alexander House
properties.ShortDescription: This house was built in 1908 for William B. Ryons, a long-time vice-president of the First National Bank in Lincoln and son of Irish-born Joseph L. Ryons, for whom Ryons Street was named. A more prominent subsequent resident was Dr. Hartley Burr Alexander, philosophy professor of the University of Nebraska. Dr. Alexander's academic achievements in the fields of philosophy, architecture, and anthropology were widely recognized, while his particular contribution to Nebraska was his involvement in organizing the thematic decoration and writing the inscriptions displayed on the Nebraska State Capitol.

properties.Name: Temple B'nai Jeshurun
properties.ShortDescription: Congregation B’nai Jeshurun was organized in Lincoln in 1884 and reflects the Reform Jewish tradition. When the congregation outgrew their earlier synagogue at 11th and D, Lincoln architects Davis & Wilson designed the new, much larger synagogue in 1923-24. The eclectic design incorporates both Byzantine and Moorish design elements in contrast to the same architects’ Gothic Revival Westminster Presbyterian church a few block east. The Temple retains a very high degree of integrity of original design on both the interior and exterior.

properties.Name: Pauley (Ray & Francis) House
properties.ShortDescription: Ray C. Pauley, secretary of his father Conrad’s Pauley Lumber Company, began this fine brick and stucco house in 1918, when he was 26 years old. A. S. Barnes is cited on the building permit as the architect. No architect by this name has been identified, but A. S. Barnes & Company was a major publisher of a wide variety of books. Possibly Ray Pauley’s design source was an A. S. Barnes publication. Lumberyards often supplied house patterns to their customers. (When his brother Ludwig built his house a block away at 2601 B Street the building permit cited “Stillwell” as the architect. E. W. Stillwell was a prolific publisher of house plan books.) Ray and his wife Frances occupied their house until his death in 1950. The house is one of Lincoln’s finest examples of Prairie School architecture, a style made popular by Frank Lloyd Wright. The rear wing, a separate apartment, was added in 1940 in the Art Deco style.

properties.Name: Gillen (Frank & Emma) House
properties.ShortDescription: The Frank and Emma Gillen House was built in 1918-19 by Fiske & Meginnis as a thorough and handsome remodeling of the Gillen’s earlier house constructed in 1903-04. The corner house is oriented with its principal entrance not to either of the adjacent streets but rather to the west where the front porch originally faced Mrs. Gillen’s renowned gardens. An apartment house now stands on the site of the gardens. Mr. Gillen operated the Gillen & Boney candy company at 8th and P in Haymarket.

properties.Name: Fawell (George & Jane) House
properties.ShortDescription: Many American houses of the early 20th century were based on the architecture of historic periods. The term "Period Revival" is used to identify a wide variety of these homes. Among the many popular sub-sets of that group were houses inspired by American Colonial (whether from New England, "Dutch" Colonial of New York, or "Spanish" Colonial from the Southwestern US), English Tudor, Italian Renaissance and French Provincial. Other "Period Revival" houses combined features of various historic periods or regions, such as the unique residence designed by Tyler, Brandt & Tyler and built in 1916 at the corner of 24th and Ryons Street by Charles Ryman for George W. Fawell, Jr. and his wife Jane. The smooth stucco walls, multitude of rounded parapets and windows, and the sweeping front stairs up to an arched center entrance all bring a touch of southern Italy, or southern California, to Lincoln, Nebraska. George Fawell, Jr. was treasurer of an investment company. His aunt, Gertrude Marquette McAfee, also had a unique house built in 1916 at 1801 C Street. Throughout the 1920s, 2401 Ryons was home to surgeon Artemus McKinnon and his family.

properties.Name: Little-Atwood House
properties.ShortDescription: The Little-Atwood House is associated with individuals who were instrumental in the development of Lincoln. Thomas P. Harrison, a leading contractor, built the house in 1894 for Frank Little, president of the Lincoln Street Railway Company. Samuel Atwood, the second owner, was a stone mason and an important local contractor. The Little-Atwood House is the earliest Neo-Classical Revival style mansion built in Lincoln, probably inspired by the Columbian Exposition in Chicago.

properties.Name: Beattie-Miles House
properties.ShortDescription: Now one of Lincoln's premier houses of the Queen Anne style, this house was built in 1892 for Professor James A. Beattie and his wife Margaret in the town of Bethany Heights, on the north edge of the Nebraska Christian University (later Cotner College) campus. Prof. Beattie served as a mathematics professor and as second president of the college prior to accepting the presidency of the State Normal College in Peru, Nebraska. The Samuel and Flora Miles family was the second to own and occupy the house, from 1901 to 1945. Their son Clarence grew up in the house, attended Harvard Law School, and became a prominent Lincoln attorney and the city's Mayor in 1947-49.

properties.Name: Wyuka Cemetery
properties.ShortDescription: Wyuka was founded by an act of the Nebraska legislature in 1869. The hilly site, originally 2 miles east of Lincoln, was laid out in a picturesque, park-like manner, following the popular trend established in 1831 by Mt. Auburn Cemetery outside Boston. From its original 40 acres the cemetery expanded by 1900 to nearly 150 acres. Historic architecture of the cemetery includes the Receiving Vault of the 1880s (designed by John H. W. Hawkins), Stable (ca. 1910, by L. A. Lamoreau), and Rudge Chapel (1936, by Davis & Wilson). Approximately 1000 Civil War veterans, over a dozen Nebraska governors, and more than 50,000 others are interred in the scenic cemetery. Information on those buried in the cemetery is available online at www.wyuka.com.

properties.Name: Whitehall (Olive White House)
properties.ShortDescription: The Neo-Classical Revival style house was built for Mrs. Olive White, widow of C. C. White, owner of the Crete Mills from 1888 to 1895. Mr. White was a member of the Nebraska Wesleyan University's Board of Trustees for many years and the couple were avid supporters of the institution. After her husband's death, Mrs. White moved to Lincoln, where she built the residence in 1910 near the Wesleyan University campus. Since 1926 the house has been used by the State of Nebraska as a home for children.

properties.Name: Bell (Jasper & Jessie) House
properties.ShortDescription: The Jasper and Jessie Bell House of 1913 was owned, occupied, and presumably built by Jasper Newton Bell, a Lincoln carpenter.  Houses of the late nineteenth and early twentieth century with square or nearly square floor plans are very common in Nebraska from one to two-and-a-half stories in height.  The Bell House stands out in this large group for its very fine Neo-Classical detailing on a modest sized house.  From the front porch with its slender, full-length Tuscan columns and low railings, to the hipped roof elaborated with wall gablets on the south and west street facades, and the dentils and crown molding at the cornices, every detail is elegant and well-executed.  Bell died in 1930 at age 85 and was interred at Wyuka Cemetery.

properties.Name: Dial (Elias & Loisa) House
properties.ShortDescription: George Ridgway was an active builder in Lincoln from around 1900 and architect by the 1910s until 1936 when he left for Spokane, Washington, passing away in 1963. Ridgway’s Dial House, built in 1904, is a small frame cottage that combines elements of the 19th century Queen Anne style and the emerging Neo-Classical Revival style of the early 20th century. It shows the influence of the new trends on even small houses, and demonstrates Ridgway's production of unique, distinctive houses by a very early point in his career. Ridgway’s client, Elias S. Dial, was a rural mail carrier.

properties.Name: Saint Charles Apartments
properties.ShortDescription: When Saint Charles Apartments were built in 1923-24, University Place was an incorporated town with a population of about 5,000. University Place was annexed by Lincoln in 1926. Saint Charles was designed to provide sixteen apartments and was the only brick apartment house built in University Place before annexation. The building, which incorporates Neo-Classical Revival motifs, was constructed by William Henry Seng, a major contractor in the University Place area during the 1920s and 1930s.

properties.Name: First State Bank of Bethany
properties.ShortDescription: Bethany was one of several towns founded around new colleges on the eastern outskirts of Nebraska's capital city in the late 19th century. From 1890 until 1926, Bethany was an independent, incorporated town with its own government, utilities, and public schools. Emblematic of that town-era is this dignified little Neo-Classical building which C. H. Larsen designed to house the First State Bank of Bethany. The building was constructed in about 1914 and the bank operated there until its failure in 1930 during the Great Depression. Later a portion of the building served as Bethany's branch library.

properties.Name: Lancaster Block
properties.ShortDescription: The Lancaster Block, constructed ca. 1890, is significant for its role in the early development of the city of Havelock. It was directly associated with the initial settlement of the town, built as the community’s first substantial business block by the land development company which platted Havelock. It was erected even before Havelock's incorporation. The building was also the venue of the strikers' meetings during the Burlington Shop strike of 1922. That strike was the major precipitating event in Havelock's decline during the 1920s, leading to its annexation by Lincoln in 1930.

properties.Name: Antelope Grocery
properties.ShortDescription: Situated just above Antelope Creek, this 1922 Tudor Revival building was designed by Fiske & Meginnis. The building successfully accommodates a mix of commercial and residential uses at a key junction point in a residential neighborhood. The original grocery store name is enshrined in stained glass over the main south entrance, and "LeRoy Apartments" is similarly displayed above the west apartment doorway.

properties.Name: Nine-Mile Prairie
properties.ShortDescription: While these 228 acres of native prairie comprise one of the largest tracts of virgin prairie remaining in eastern Nebraska, Nine-Mile Prairie derives its historical significance and National Register status as the site of more than 40 years of pioneering studies of scientific plant ecology by Dr. John E. Weaver and students at the University of Nebraska. Weaver, the "founding father of modern plant ecology," began his study of the prairie in 1917. In the 1920s the prairie was a site for University of Nebraska student research projects under Weaver's direction. The prairie continues as a research and educational site for students and conservation groups. The prairie was so named in the 1930s because of its location nine miles from downtown Lincoln.

properties.Name: Hayward School
properties.ShortDescription: Hayward School was built in 1903-04, with additions completed in 1913 and 1925. Each building phase displays a distinct style of public school architecture. The original school is at the center of the present structure and was designed by architect James H. Craddock, with Late Renaissance Revival detailing. The south addition of 1913 was the work of Berlinghof & Davis and displays simplified Neo-Classical elements. The long north addition of 1925 by Fiske, Meginnis & Schaumberg has a fine Colonial Revival entryway on the north. The school served the German Russian community of the North Bottoms through citizenship classes for adults and by operating a special program for the "beet field children" whose school year was shortened while working in the sugar beet fields of western Nebraska. In the mid-1980s the school was converted to more than three dozen condominium apartments.

properties.Name: President & Ambassador Apartments
properties.ShortDescription: The President & Ambassador Apartments are a pair of five-story, flat-roofed, apartment buildings. They were constructed in 1928-29 by architect/developer John M. Alexander of reinforced concrete with red brick veneer and limestone trim. They are very prominently sited adjacent to the State Capitol and acknowledge this important siting in several design features. The east side of the President facing the Capitol displays richly carved Art Deco limestone trim. Both buildings offer fine south porches with limestone arcades facing the boulevard connection between the Capitol and local government campus (now called Lincoln Mall). Together the twin buildings enclose a distinctive courtyard enhanced by a renovation in 2015.

properties.Name: Lancaster County Poor Farm Residence (Westview)
properties.ShortDescription: The Poor Farm residence of 1916 is of architectural interest for its fireproof construction and its design by John G. Cordner with his apparent attempt to “domesticate” an institutional building. The scarcity of major historic buildings constructed by Lancaster County adds to the importance of the Poor Farm. The County operated it as a nursing home called Westview from 1952-76. The primary significance of the building is associational, as a tangible reminder of the County’s early system of social welfare.

properties.Name: Lincoln Army Air Field Chapel
properties.Architect: Office of the Quartermaster General, US Army
properties.ShortDescription: Following the December 7, 1941 attack on Pearl Harbor and the declaration of war, eleven large army air fields were rapidly constructed in Nebraska in the single year 1942, including Lincoln Army Air Field (LAAF) five miles northwest of Lincoln. This rapid mobilization was facilitated by the fact that the U. S. military had previously developed standardized plans for building such bases in response to the worsening international conflicts in Europe and Asia. Initially religious services were intended to be held in theaters and recreation halls, but Eleanor Roosevelt intervened, arguing that military chapels would boost morale. Therefore the Office of the Quartermaster General of the Army included colonial revival style chapels in their standardized air field plans. All of these buildings were designed for rapid construction—the Lincoln chapel took just 21 days to build—and were intended to be temporary. Hence the LAAF Chapel is a very rare example from a WWII Army air field.

properties.Name: East Lincoln Baptist Church
properties.ShortDescription: This Neo-Classical Revival church was highly innovative when it was built in 1907 for its use of concrete blocks as its primary building material. Concrete blocks were becoming common in early 20th century Lincoln for foundations and retaining walls, but relatively few houses and only a tiny number of churches utilized it for whole buildings. This church further demonstrates architects Fiske & Dieman's scope of practice in terms of building types, styles, and materials.

properties.Name: LT&T #4 Exchange (National Museum of Roller Skating)
properties.ShortDescription: The Lincoln Telephone & Telegraph #4 Exchange demonstrates the Colonial Revival style of architecture applied to a utility building. Designed by the prominent Lincoln architectural firm of Davis & Wilson in 1936, the building is solidly constructed of fine materials. In its materials and style, the building was designed for compatibility with its residential setting. Since 1989, the building has housed the National Museum of Roller Skating.

properties.Name: Saint Francis Chapel
properties.ShortDescription: Saint Francis Church was built in 1921 as a chapel wing of St. Elizabeth Hospital, the first of Lincoln’s general hospitals. The chapel was design by Jacob Nachtigall of Omaha. The main wings of the old hospital were demolished in the 1990s, leaving the chapel and its bell tower freestanding. A new façade was constructed in 1994. The simple exterior belies the elaborate ornament of the interior which is the best surviving example in Lincoln of an early 20th century, ornate Gothic Revival ecclesiastical space. The stained glass windows are an especially noteworthy feature.

properties.Name: Pioneers Park
properties.ShortDescription: Pioneers Park, located just outside Lincoln, is significant for its association with local and federal unemployment relief programs. The park benefited from local unemployment relief programs, implemented in the late 1920s followed by federal programs of the 1930s including the Works Progress Administration, the National Youth Administration, and the Civil Works Administration—programs established during the Great Depression to provide employment in public works of lasting value. Lincoln landscape architect Ernst Herman Herminghaus designed the original 500 acre park with distinctive features such as tree-lined allees framing distant vistas, winding roads, path systems, and sculptural focal points. Views from the park to the Capitol tower are a hallmark of the design. Work on the park began in 1928 with the final historically significant components of the original plan being implemented in 1939. Pinewood Bowl was constructed as a World War II memorial but a similar feature was included in the original plans.

properties.Name: Fairview (William Jennings & Mary Bryan House)
properties.ShortDescription: Roberts & Woods designed Mary and William Jennings Bryan's country mansion with a combination of Queen Anne and Neo-Classical Revival features. The house was constructed in 1902 and 1903. While the house is architecturally distinguished, its greater significance derives from William's prominence as a U. S. Congressman, three-time presidential candidate, and durable national political figure. In 1922, the Bryans gave the house and ten-acres of their farm to the Methodist Church to create a hospital. Upon his death in 1925, the family granted the request that the hospital bear the name "Bryan Memorial Hospital."

properties.Name: Old Main at Nebraska Wesleyan University
properties.ShortDescription: Nebraska Wesleyan University was founded in the town of University Place in 1887. To house the new university this three-story Richardsonian Romanesque structure was constructed in 1887-88, designed by architects Gibbs & Parker of Kansas City. Wesleyan’s "Old Main" is more than a campus landmark, because Wesleyan was one of half a dozen colleges established on the outskirts of Lincoln in the 1880s and 1890s. Only Nebraska Wesleyan and Union College remain of those institutions and only Old Main recalls the grand structures that housed each of them.

properties.Name: Delta Gamma Sorority
properties.ShortDescription: Delta Gamma was built in 1926 by designs from Davis & Wilson. Delta Gamma and Kappa Delta sororities flank University Terrace on the north side of R Street between 16th and 17th Streets, defining a lovely open space between the two brick Tudor Revival residences. Together with Alpha Xi Delta and Delta Delta Delta on the south side of R Street, these four sororities form a strong southeast corner of the Greek Row District.

properties.Name: Kappa Kappa Gamma Sorority
properties.ShortDescription: Kappa Kappa Gamma was the first sorority established at the University of Nebraska, dating from 1884. The house is an excellent representative of the several Period Revival chapter houses designed by the prominent Lincoln architects Miller & Craig. The Kappa Kappa Gamma Sorority house is a central element of the 16th Street core of the “Greek Row” district, located just north of Raymond Hall/Neihardt Center. The two and a half story structure is a skillful rendition of the Tudor Revival style. The principal, west facade originally featured the main entrance via a brick porch at the north side. The porch remains but its openings have been infilled with masonry.

properties.Name: Hitchcock (William & Birdie) House
properties.ShortDescription: The Hitchcock House is a two-and-one-half story Colonial Revival style residence constructed in 1922 for an auto dealer and his family. Local architect Jesse Boaz Miller designed this symmetrical, stucco-clad house, which features a central block with a green tile roof, and flat-roofed side wings. In addition, there is a matching carriage house and extensive early landscaping, including border hedges outlining the curbs and front sidewalks. Early photographs document that these hedges were a common treatment along this portion of Sheridan Boulevard.

properties.Name: Sigma Phi Epsilon Fraternity
properties.ShortDescription: The Sigma Phi Epsilon house was constructed in 1929 in a high Tudor Revival manner by the Lincoln architects Miller & Craig. On its constricted site a major addition was added in 1967 on the northeast side in the front yard, carefully designed by Clark & Enersen, Olsson, Burroughs & Thomsen in the spirit of the original building. In 2017 construction began on major additions to the east and south facades, again well-designed by Clark Architects Collaborative 3 to follow the original style and materials.

properties.Name: Old City Hall
properties.ShortDescription: Old City Hall stands on the block designated on Lincoln's original city plan of 1867 as "Market Square," which was initially planned as a stopping point for visitors and an open-air market for residents. In 1873 the City deeded the block to the U. S. Government to induce the construction of a properly monumental federal courthouse and post office, befitting a state capital. The richly textured limestone building at 916 O Street was the result, constructed between 1873 and 1879 and now known as Old City Hall reflecting its use from 1907 to 1969. Alfred B. Mullett was the original architect, in his role as "Supervising Architect of the Treasury." That office in Washington, D.C. was responsible for designing buildings all over the country for the U. S. Government. Mullett began the building of Gage County (Nebr.) limestone in his preferred French Second Empire style, which typically would have included smooth limestone walls, abundant classical columns and a mansard roof. But Mullett was replaced in 1875 as Supervising Architect by William Appleton Potter, who preferred the "High Victorian Gothic" style, which utilized Gothic detailing and sometimes multiple colors of brick and stone. Potter kept to Mullett's mansard roof and single color of masonry, but followed his own preference in the rich texture of the stonework and Gothic detailing. The building remains in City ownership and the interior features a cast iron main staircase and one of Lincoln's oldest operating elevators. In 1978 restoration began, and the building is now used by civic groups.

properties.Name: Old Federal Building (Grand Manse)
properties.ShortDescription: In 1905, a new federal building was under construction on the east (10th Street) end of the north half of Government Square, designed by federal architect James Knox Taylor. Taylor only built the east wing of the building, but his east facade set the style and basic materials followed by the middle (1914-15) and west (1939-41) portions. Together, the three parts result in a building which appears highly unified considering it was constructed in three campaigns spanning more than three decades. Inside, the different periods of construction are more apparent. The east wing retains fine materials in the corridors and the third floor courtroom features rich oak woodwork, an ornate plasterwork ceiling, and the original judge's bench. In this courtroom in 1974, Federal Judge Warren Urbom presided over the cases of more than 130 defendants arising from the 1973 occupation of Wounded Knee, South Dakota. “Old Fed” was sold to private owners in 2003 and converted to apartments and a mix of commercial uses.

properties.Name: Stake (Reese & Emma) House
properties.ShortDescription: The Stake House is an outstanding example of a bungalow, designed by a leading Lincoln architect, George Berlinghof, and constructed in 1919 with exceptional durability and finish by a local builder, Reese O. Stake, for his own family. The house features reinforced concrete construction clad in brick and limestone, green glazed roof tiles, and stuccoed soffits.

properties.Name: Lally (Frank & Mary) House
properties.ShortDescription: The Lally House of 1889 is the centerpiece of a significant ensemble of Queen Anne style houses demonstrating development on the east terrace above Antelope Creek during the 1880s, the city’s decade of most explosive growth.  The flanking Pace-Woods House and Murphy-Sheldon House are larger and more ornate than the Lally cottage but the smaller house completes the important grouping. The first owner-occupants in the early 20th century were Frank Lally, a janitor at the University Farm, and his daughter Eleanor Lally, a teacher at nearby Elliot School.

properties.Name: Lyman Terrace
properties.ShortDescription: Lincoln's population burgeoned from about 13,000 in 1880 to 55,000 in 1890. Among the new, urban buildings developed in the booming city were a small number of row houses–multi-story homes, each with its own entrance, sharing party walls. Ferdinand C. Fiske designed the neighboring Barr Terrace and the limestone-faced Lyman Terrace, built in 1890. Charles C. Lyman was a lumberman in several southeastern Nebraska communities before erecting and residing in the terrace. Like Lincoln's other row houses, Lyman Terrace was soon divided into apartments.

properties.Name: Kappa Sigma Fraternity
properties.ShortDescription: Kappa Sigma Fraternity house, built in 1924-25, is the only known Lincoln work by the prominent Omaha architects McDonald & McDonald. It is also atypical among Greek chapter houses of the 1920s in that it was not built in the growing Greek Row area of R and 16th Streets adjacent to the expanding University of Nebraska campus, but instead followed the earlier pattern of locating in the residential neighborhoods south and southeast of the Capitol. The brown brick house with limestone trim resembles many of the campus-side Greek houses in employing Period Revival style, with "Jacobethan" features. These include the very steep roof, Flemish bond brickwork with rough "waster" bricks mixed in to add texture, and stone label moldings over the windows. Kappa Sigma moved to a newly built house in Greek Row in 1955.

properties.Name: Phi Delta Theta Fraternity
properties.ShortDescription: When Greek Row developed on the south and east edges of the expanded University of Nebraska city campus, the chapter houses of the 1910s and ‘20s reflected revivals of historic architectural styles, especially Tudor and Colonial. In contrast, Phi Delta Theta of 1937 displays the more innovative Art Moderne style in its sleek limestone exterior and curved glass block corner. Lincoln architect Martin I. Aitken was responsible for the design. At night the curved staircase within the illuminated glass corner makes this a focal point at a prominent campus intersection.

properties.Name: Kappa Alpha Theta Sorority
properties.ShortDescription: Kappa Alpha Theta Sorority house is one of the best examples within the Greek Row Historic District of Federal Revival style architecture, and was designed in 1925 by Davis & Wilson, Lincoln’s leading architectural firm at that time. The two and a half story red brick building at the southwest corner of 16th and S Streets has a gambrel roof of slate with shed dormers providing a third story. The house is oriented with its main entrance and semi-circular Doric portico facing to the west, towards Alpha Omicron Pi (1541 S Street). Together the two sororities create a small courtyard off S Street.

properties.Name: Alpha Xi Delta Sorority
properties.ShortDescription: This tall limestone sorority house was built in 1929 and anchors the southeast corner of the Greek Row Historic District. Its architects, Miller & Craig, designed ten of the chapter houses within that district, often in the Tudor Revival style of Alpha Xi. An east addition of 1967 by Woodrow Hull is well-designed to be both subordinate and complementary to the original building.

properties.Name: Delta Delta Delta Sorority
properties.ShortDescription: Miller & Craig were the most prolific architects of Greek chapter houses at UNL. The "Tri-Delt" house at the prominent southeast corner of 16th and R Streets exemplifies their fine work in the Tudor Revival style. The wrought-iron fence surrounding the property was donated to the sorority by General John J. Pershing, whose sister Mae had been a member. The house was built in 1926 by T. Randolph and enlarged in 1971 to the south with a design very carefully echoing the initial design in style and material.

properties.Name: Sigma Nu Fraternity
properties.ShortDescription: Sigma Nu is unique in UNL’s Greek Row in utilizing the Spanish Colonial style with a strong symmetrical façade, arcaded entrance, and tile roof. The building was executed in 1927 by prominent Omaha architect N. R. Brigham and Lincoln builder John M. Alexander & Co.

properties.Name: Murphy-Sheldon House
properties.ShortDescription: The Murphy-Sheldon House was built around 1889 near the eastern edge of Lincoln. It is a fine example of the newly-popular, richly decorative Queen Anne style and is noteworthy for retaining its elaborate main porch, carriage porch, carriage house, and interior elements. The first owners, William L. and Sydney V. Murphy, worked in real estate. It was later the home of Frances Sheldon, a patron of the arts in Lincoln whose major bequest to the University of Nebraska resulted in the Sheldon Museum of Art.

properties.Name: Pace-Woods House
properties.ShortDescription: The Queen Anne style Pace-Woods House of 1886 was originally the home of the L. C. Pace family. Their daughter Clarke married Mark Woods and the new family made their home there as well.  Mark and his brothers Frank and George established several Lincoln businesses as the Woods Brothers. Their enterprises included real estate, importing of draft stallions, Lincoln Telephone & Telegraph Company, and Woods Aitken law firm.

properties.Name: Hall (Frank & Anna) House
properties.ShortDescription: Banker Richard Outcalt built the large wood-frame house designed by John H. W. Hawkins at the northwest corner of 11th and D Streets around 1884. Attorney Frank M. Hall and his wife Anna purchased the property in 1894 and resided here until their deaths in 1928. Mr. Hall was a prominent attorney and supporter of University of Nebraska. He and Mrs. Hall were active in the local art community as collectors and leaders in organizations such as Nebraska Art Association. Their bequest established the Hall Collection, now the foundation of Sheldon Museum of Art. The Halls remodeled the wrap-around porch in the early 20th century and made a north addition, as well as enclosing the yard in a brick and iron fence. The gazebo was designed for the Halls by Chicago architect Paul V. Hyland in 1911.

properties.Name: Mt. Zion Baptist Church (Lincoln Baptist Church)
properties.ShortDescription: Mt. Zion Baptist Church, a predominantly African-American congregation, received this lot at the southeast corner of 12th and F Streets from the State of Nebraska in 1883. They first occupied a wood-frame church, then constructed a limestone basement in 1892 above which the present sanctuary was added in 1922. James Tyler, Jr. designed the Mission Style church with its characteristic stepped and curved parapets and stuccoed brick walls. The original congregation moved to a larger facility at 3301 N. 56th St. in 1991.

properties.Name: Helmer-Winnett-White Flats
properties.ShortDescription: As Lincoln became a larger and more urbanized place in the 1880s and 1890s new housing types began to be developed. Previously in Lincoln typical housing types included single family, duplex, boarding houses, and residential hotels. In the late 1880s row houses began to be built in Lincoln. Two surviving examples are Barr Terrace and Lyman Terrace, nearby at 11th and H Streets. A terrace or row house building combines multiple dwellings, each of which has its own entrance and occupies multiple floors. Flats were an alternative type of multi-family housing in which each home typically had its own entrance but only occupied one floor. The Helmer-Winnett-White Flats, built circa 1898 displays four entrances for the four units, each of which occupied half of one floor. While the building has been occupied by offices for several decades, the ornate residential façade still displays limestone trim, complex brickwork, and a pressed metal cornice. Louis Helmer served as County Treasurer, State legislator, and on the Lincoln school board. H. J. Winnett, a pioneer Lincoln physician, was elected mayor in 1899. William T. White owned the underlying land.

properties.Name: Lincoln Woman's Club
properties.ShortDescription: While the clubhouse of the Lincoln Woman’s Club is a pristine small-scale example of International style architecture designed by Lincoln architectural firm Schaumberg & Freeman, its primary significance derives from its association with a distinguished local institution. The Lincoln Woman’s Club, formed in 1894, had from its inception actively worked for the betterment of the Lincoln community by raising funds for charities. The club also provided educational opportunities to its members and leadership in regard to issues specifically impacting women. Construction began in 1954 and the building was dedicated in 1955.

properties.Name: Krull (Frederick & Dora) House
properties.ShortDescription: An account of the construction of the house, written in 1903 by William Krull, son of the builder Frederick Krull, dates the house to either 1868 or 1870 and identifies a quarry near Roca as the source of the limestone. Although vacant for many years, the house retains its massive limestone walls, wooden roofs, and brick chimneys. Only a few limestone houses of this era are extant in Lancaster County, notably the Retzlaff House near Stevens Creek in the east-central part of the county, constructed in 1867 and listed on the National Register of Historic Places, and the William Keys Mansion in Roca. Krull House is a significant, rare, endangered historic resource of our community.

properties.Name: AT&T Switching Station
properties.ShortDescription: Built in 1941 on a rural hilltop as part of AT&T’s nationwide long-distance telephone network, this reinforced concrete utility building is clad in red brick with limestone trim. Its simple decorative features are Colonial Revival in style. Overall, the building resembles a country schoolhouse, befitting its setting. It was designed by the architects Kimball, Steele & Sandham of Omaha, successor firm to Thomas R. Kimball (1862-1934).

properties.Name: Eddy-Taylor House
properties.ShortDescription: The brick house is one of Lincoln’s best examples of the Queen Anne style with a particularly noteworthy porch.  It was constructed about 1891 by a local developer, Ambrose Eddy, and was owned and occupied by him and his son Everett and their families. It was built as the show home and office of the Eddys’ subdivision. The Eddys also built the four houses immediately south of this house. The Eddys sold the house in 1902 to William George Langworthy Taylor, a distinguished member of the University of Nebraska faculty. Taylor was a graduate of Harvard and also studied in Europe. He was head of University of Nebraska’s political economy department, as well as a prolific author, world traveler, and horseman. The house served fraternities and sororities in the 1910s and ‘20s. Because of its size, scale, and materials, the house dominates its streetscape and neighborhood.

properties.Name: Old University Library (Architecture Hall)
properties.ShortDescription: The Old University Library, constructed 1891-95, is the oldest existing building on the University of Nebraska-Lincoln's downtown campus. Designed by the architectural firm of Mendelssohn, Fisher & Lawrie of Omaha in the Richardsonian Romanesque style, the building served as the University’s library until replaced by Love Library in 1945. It subsequently housed the College of Architecture. A major renovation in 1985-87 linked the old library and the old Law College to the west. Bahr, Vermeer & Haecker were the architects, having won a competition held in 1978. The College of Architecture now includes programs in Architecture, Interior Design, Landscape Architecture, and Community & Regional Planning.

properties.Name: Woods Brothers Companies Building
properties.ShortDescription: Col. F. M. Woods, a livestock auctioneer from Illinois, brought his family to Lincoln in the 1870s. Three of his sons, Mark, George, and Frank Woods, began forming a series of companies in 1889 dealing in real estate, livestock, and construction. Under the umbrella title of “The Woods Brothers Companies” they played a major role in real estate development of Lincoln. Their offices were at 719 P Street near the railroad depot until 1916 when the Woods Brothers Construction Company completed this small office building in the heart of Lincoln’s financial and commercial district. The new headquarters was adjacent to the Nebraska Telephone Company Building which another of their companies, Lincoln Telephone & Telegraph, had recently acquired. This was the home office of the Woods Brothers Companies until 1939.

properties.Name: Weil (Morris & Ida) House
properties.ShortDescription: Built in 1902 by Oliver P. Harrison, the Weil House is one of Lincoln’s finest Neo-Classical Revival style houses. It was built for Morris Weil and occupied by him and his family for half a century. Weil was the founder of Bank of Commerce, later named National Bank of Commerce or NBC Bank.  After the Weil family moved out the house became a nursing home, then was rehabilitated as a Bed & Breakfast Inn and now is home to a UNL fraternity.

properties.Name: Kiesselbach (Theodore & Hazel) House
properties.ShortDescription: The Kiesselbach House, designed by architect John R. Smith and constructed in 1913, is significant for its association with Dr. Theodore Alexander Kiesselbach, a University of Nebraska agronomist and a pioneering Nebraska researcher in corn and other crops. Called “Mr. Corn,” he developed corn hybrids that significantly increased farm production and income throughout the state. Kiesselbach Hall on UNL’s east campus is named for Dr. Kiesselbach.

properties.Name: Ricketts (Arnott & Elizabeth) House
properties.ShortDescription: Prominent Lincoln attorney, Arnott Ricketts, and his first wife Louisa lived in a large Queen Anne mansion at 33rd and L Streets, then beyond the east edge of Lincoln. He was widowed in 1902 and upon his remarriage to Elizabeth in 1909, they moved into the established neighborhood at 22nd and B Streets. Their brand-new house exemplifies the American Foursquare form, with a full length porch, cubic massing, and high hipped roof with hipped dormers. The house was designated as an individual landmark in 1994 to allow its utilization as part of the Rogers House B & B.

properties.Name: Rogers (Noyes & Harriet) House
properties.ShortDescription: Lincoln’s first Bed & Breakfast Inn occupies the 1914 mansion of Noyes and Harriet Rogers. Fiske & Miller designed the Jacobethan Revival house with subtle complexity in the brickwork and stone ornament, varied wall and roof planes, and a carriage porch with stepped parapet on the west side. Noyes C. Rogers, a banker from Minden, Nebraska, was director of Lincoln’s Central National Bank.

properties.Name: Candy (Albert & Ella) House
properties.ShortDescription: Constructed in 1888 by T. P. Quick and expanded in 1907 by contractor George A. Wilson, this small house is significant as the residence of Professor Albert Luther Candy, a "Professor of Pure Mathematics" at University of Nebraska and chairman of the Mathematics Department from 1918 to 1935. His active teaching career at UNL spanned from 1893 to 1935, when he retired to emeritus status at age 78. Professor Candy was not only a prominent mathematician, but also a Lincoln alderman and a long-time member of the Board of Social Welfare.

properties.Name: Woods (Frank & Nelle) House
properties.ShortDescription: The Frank and Nelle Woods House, constructed in 1915-16, is a uniquely large and well preserved example of the Italian Renaissance Revival style in Lincoln. Designed by Chicago architect Paul V. Hyland, the house is situated on a very large urban lot. The grounds were laid out by the nationally prominent landscape architect Jens Jensen, who also designed the surrounding Woodscrest Addition for the Woods Brothers Company. The property retains a high degree of interior and exterior integrity, as well as significant features of its designed landscape.

properties.Name: Lau (Alexander & Margaret) House
properties.ShortDescription: Alexander Christian Lau had this handsome house built in 1907, a few months before he married Margaret Honeywell.  The house stands on one of the large lots of the Honeywell Place addition, which was platted by Margaret's brother H. H. Honeywell in 1907.  His house was built directly east of hers around 1911, and her parents were the Laus' north neighbors after 1913.  A. C. Lau was a vice president in his family’s H. P. Lau Company, grocery wholesalers in Haymarket.  This remained the family home into the 1950s.

properties.Name: Roberts (Charles & Elizabeth) House
properties.ShortDescription: The Charles and Elizabeth Roberts House was constructed for the family of a prominent Lincoln builder, but is even more significant as one of the last works in this area of Charles’ father, architect Artemas Roberts (1841-1944). Artemas contributed such significant designs to Lincoln’s built environment as the original Lincoln High School, Herpolsheimer’s department store, and Fairview. The Roberts House demonstrates his father’s continued architectural ability at age 75. The large and well-preserved house and yard reflect the economic success and stature of the second generation of this important Lincoln family.

properties.Name: CB&Q Locomotive 710
properties.ShortDescription: One of the few remaining steam locomotives built at Burlington Railroad's Havelock Shops, the 78 ton Locomotive 710 was constructed in 1901 and rebuilt in 1928 with smaller drive wheels in a 4-6-0 configuration. It was used first in passenger service, then for mixed freight loads from 1928-1950. Donated to the City of Lincoln in 1955, it was displayed at Pioneers Park until 1991, when it was repaired and relocated to Track 1, adjacent the Burlington Depot (Lincoln Station) in the Haymarket Historic District.

properties.Name: First National Bank Building
properties.ShortDescription: First National Bank was Lincoln's first federally chartered bank in 1871 and was one of the few local banks to survive the turbulent 1890s. In 1910 the bank replaced its 1870's building on the southeast corner of 10th and O Streets with an eight-story, steel-frame structure, designed by the Chicago architects Hyland & Green. For half a decade the Commercial Style structure was Lincoln's tallest office building, until it was superseded by two ten-story structures in 1915 and 1916. (See Security Mutual Building and Terminal Building, the latter designed by Paul V. Hyland formerly of Hyland & Green.) It remains a handsome example of the national influence of Chicago architecture.

properties.Name: Palisade & Regent Apartments
properties.ShortDescription: The Palisade & Regent Apartments are significant examples of the large and ornate apartments built at the end of Lincoln's second historic apartment "boom" of the 1920s. They are noteworthy for their rare use of terra cotta block as a primary building material. The five-story Palisade was completed first (in 1928) and is oriented to 17th Street with a U-shaped plan embracing the recessed entry. Construction of the four-story Regent followed in 1929. The Regent is oriented to D Street with a simpler, rectangular plan but more ornate terra cotta decoration. The third structure of the original complex, on the alley north of the Regent, was constructed as a plain, brick parking garage but has been modified into apartments.  Harry Goldstein was the designer and developer of this complex.

properties.Name: Hurlbut-Yates House
properties.ShortDescription: Built in 1891 from a design by architect Ferdinand C. Fiske, the Hurlbut-Yates House is prominently located on a large corner lot near the Capitol. The house is a two-and-one-half story frame Queen Anne residence with Eastlake-type spindle work. The house retains a high degree of integrity in its elaborate detailing, massing, and extensive ornate porches. The house was built for Aeneas Hurlbut, a Civil War veteran, clothier, land developer, and hotel promoter. When economic conditions worsened in 1893, Hurlbut apparently could no longer afford his large new house and traded with Charles and Ruth Yates for their smaller home. Charles Yates was a prominent figure in Lincoln commerce, banking, and railroad circles from the 1870s into the 1920s.

properties.Name: Brown (Guy & Mary) House
properties.ShortDescription: Only about a half-dozen houses remain in Lincoln from the city's first decade. The Brown House of 1874 is an unusual version of the Italianate style, with a facade gable above a projecting entrance, and a paneled cornice, rather than the typical brackets. The brick porch is an early 20th century addition. Guy Brown served in the early state government of Nebraska as State Librarian and Clerk and Reporter of the Supreme Court. The much larger Queen Anne style house just south of 219-221 South Street was built by Guy and Mary Brown just before his death in 1890.

properties.Name: Spalding (Frank & Julia) House
properties.ShortDescription: The Frank and Julia Spalding House was constructed between 1908 and 1910 as the first house built on the Woods Brothers' Sheridan Boulevard development. Construction commenced even before the land was platted and streets were graded in 1909. Fiske & Dieman designed the Mission Revival style building, constructed in quarry-faced Colorado red sandstone. Frank Spalding was a lumber dealer and the home’s interior displays high-quality woodwork. The house was listed individually on the National Register in 1999 and contributes to the Boulevards Historic District.

properties.Name: Quinn Chapel African Methodist Episcopal Church
properties.ShortDescription: Quinn Chapel A. M. E. Church was established in 1871 as Lincoln's first African-American congregation. Their first church was located at 1024-26 E Street on land granted by the State of Nebraska. They subsequently built a brick church at 1026 F Street in 1900, then moved that structure to 9th and C in 1915. Finally, Lincoln architect A. W. Woods designed an enlargement, remodeling, and new corner tower in 1926, establishing the overall appearance that remains into the 21st century. Many of Lincoln's residents of African ancestry lived south and southwest of downtown Lincoln in the late 19th and early 20th centuries, before residential segregation prevailed in the 1920s and later, establishing an African-American enclave around 20th and T Streets.

properties.Name: Ross (Nimrod & Ella) House
properties.ShortDescription: The Ross House in the Woods Park neighborhood is a small, single-story wood-frame cottage constructed in 1903.  Nimrod Ross was an early African-American police officer and his son Clinton was the first African-American law graduate of the University of Nebraska as well as a student athlete. It is significant for its association with the evolving patterns of educational opportunity and employment discrimination for African-Americans in the community.

properties.Name: Burckhardt (Rev. Oliver & Anna) House
properties.ShortDescription: Two of Lincoln's most influential and beloved African-American residents built this house in 1903 and made their home here until 1945. Anna Burckhardt was a well-known artist and art teacher. Her husband Rev. Oliver J. served congregations across Nebraska, was associate chaplain at the State Penitentiary, and helped charter Lincoln's branch of the NAACP in 1918. He supported his family as a porter and waiter.

properties.Name: McWilliams (Rev. Trago & Ida Belle) House
properties.ShortDescription: This small, single-story wood-frame cottage, constructed in 1890 in the Clinton neighborhood, has significance for its residents rather than its architecture. Reverend Trago T. McWilliams was a son of John Jefferson and Sarah McWilliams, founders of a large and longstanding Lincoln family. Trago T. and Ida Belle McWilliams were advocates for the betterment of Lincoln’s African-American community. He was an entrepreneur, churchman, and civil rights leader, recognized by governors, mayors, and the broader Lincoln community. Their son Rev. Trago O. McWilliams served similar roles in the following generation. Trago Park honors both father and son.

properties.Name: Federal Trust Building
properties.ShortDescription: The Federal Trust Building is a well-preserved representative of a significant moment in Lincoln office construction, built in 1926-27 and designed by the productive local architecture firm of Meginnis & Schaumberg. With its contemporaries, the Sharp Building immediately to the south and the Stuart Building a block to the north, Federal Trust gave 13th Street a new scale of tall office buildings and positioned 13th and O as downtown Lincoln’s centerpiece. The Federal Trust Building displays the Gothic Revival style in a more focused manner than any other Lincoln office building and especially noteworthy is the two story cap of limestone crowned with a tall terra cotta cornice of Gothic crockets and finials. On the interior, a marble lobby leads to a splendid bank-room on the east side with marble piers and tall Gothic windows.

properties.Name: Stuart Building (University Towers)
properties.ShortDescription: The Stuart Building was designed by Lincoln architects Davis & Wilson and completed in 1929 in the Art Deco style with Gothic Revival ornament including gargoyles. Charles Stuart developed the building to include retail, a major movie theater, first-class offices, and a private club on the top levels.

properties.Name: Yost (John & Christina) House
properties.ShortDescription: Located in Franklin Heights, the Yost House was built in 1912 by Nathan Bishop from designs by George A. Berlinghof. The two-and-one-half-story Italian Renaissance Revival style residence features a red tile hipped roof, broad eaves, and heavy brackets. John H. Yost was born in Norka, Russia to German parents and established several lumber yards in Nebraska. His house is emblematic of an American immigrant’s rags-to-riches story.

properties.Name: Thayer (Gov. John & Mary) House
properties.ShortDescription: Midway through his service as Nebraska’s Governor, John and Mary Thayer purchased this imposing Queen Anne style residence from architect George W. Peters for their Lincoln home. Peters began its construction about 1887 with builder John F. Harrison and resided in the house until he sold it to the Thayers in 1889. Thayer’s earlier service to the State included organizing and leading Nebraska’s First Regiment in the Civil War and serving as one of the first U. S. Senators from the new state in 1867. Mr. Thayer resided in the house until his death in 1906.

properties.Name: Masonic Temple
properties.ShortDescription: Designed by the Lincoln architectural firm of Meginnis & Schaumberg and built in 1935, the Masonic Temple is an excellent example of the union of art and architecture. A restrained Art Deco style is seen in the cubic massing and geometric décor of the building. Locally renowned artist Elizabeth Honor Dolan contributed significantly to the building's interior, creating a series of nine related murals in the meeting hall. The bas relief sculpture above the main entrance to the Masonic Temple was also based on a sketch by Dolan.

properties.Name: Comfort Station
properties.ShortDescription: The third, smallest building on Government Square, at the corner of 9th and O Streets, was built in 1924 as a "Public Comfort Station for Men," especially for travelers on the DLD (Detroit-Lincoln-Denver) Highway. Women's restrooms were provided in the City Hall next door. Fritz Craig designed the limestone structure to be compatible with the Federal Building north of it and to provide not only restrooms, but also shoe shining and a cigar stand. Trago T. McWilliams, later a minister and civil rights leader in Lincoln, was one of a succession of African-American men who operated the comfort station and concessions in its early decades.

properties.Name: Burnett (Edgar & Nellie) House
properties.ShortDescription: Edgar A. Burnett was associate dean of agriculture in 1904 when he commissioned Fiske & Dieman to design this large American Foursquare house on a splendid lot near the University of Nebraska's agricultural campus. Dr. Burnett and wife, former English professor Nellie Folsom, remained in the house through his service as the University's Chancellor from 1927-1938.

properties.Name: Phi Kappa Tau Fraternity (NWU)
properties.ShortDescription: The Phi Kappa Tau fraternity house of Nebraska Wesleyan University is a two-and-one-half story, red brick Period Revival structure designed by architects Meginnis & Schaumberg, with Frank Robey serving as contractor. The “Greek system” was formally recognized at Wesleyan in 1920, and the Phi Kappa Tau house was constructed in 1928. While several of Wesleyan’s fraternities and sororities were short-lived or experienced difficulty acquiring a permanent residence, Phi Kappa Tau persevered and managed to remain in their original chapter house. The Phi Kappa Tau house is the only original Greek chapter house at Nebraska Wesleyan University that retains historic integrity.

properties.Name: College View Public Library
properties.ShortDescription: This library building of 1914 was one of five in Lincoln and surrounding towns (that became parts of Lincoln) constructed with the financial assistance of Andrew Carnegie. Carnegie grants included requirements that resulted in similarities among many of these libraries, but local architects also gave each its own unique characteristics. Lincoln architect John G. Cordner prepared the Neo-Classical Revival design for this buff brick and limestone library that served the town of College View from the corner of the Union College campus.

properties.Name: Christian Record Building
properties.ShortDescription: The Christian Record was a Braille publishing house associated with the Seventh Day Adventist Church. The enterprise was located in the town of College View, Nebraska in 1904 for proximity to the church's Union College. Six years after College View became part of Lincoln by annexation in 1930, the publishing house moved into new quarters with an Art Deco-style limestone facade designed and built by Felix Lorenz. Christian Record occupied the building until 1965.

properties.Name: Trinity Methodist Episcopal Church
properties.ShortDescription: Trinity Methodist Episcopal Church was the second major Methodist congregation in Lincoln, founded in 1878, reflecting the city’s growth and southward development.  The early growth of the congregation and the first two building campaigns in 1893 and 1910 are closely associated with Rev. Dr. Dewitt Clinton Huntington, who also shepherded the early growth of Nebraska Wesleyan University.  Architecturally, Trinity assembles three major wings of distinct styles and periods into a unified whole. The earliest portion was built at the northeast corner of the property against the alley, reserving the prominent corner of 16th and A Streets. In 1910 the Cleveland church architects Badgley & Nicklas filled in the corner with the Gothic Revival tower and main sanctuary. The education wing to the west was built in the International style in 1957.

properties.Name: Heidenreich (Charles & Augusta) House
properties.ShortDescription: The Heidenreich House is a well-preserved, archetypal example of a very important house type in Lincoln, the early 20th century American Foursquare (or “Prairie Box”). Its corner location, excellent preservation and maintenance, and enhanced features such as leaded glass windows, bay window, and interior woodwork display all the features of that house type. G. J. Flory built the house in 1912 for cigar-maker Charles Heidenreich. The second owner of the residence, Trinity Lutheran Church, and the house’s use for more than two decades as that congregation’s parsonage, add to the significance of the house by association. Trinity was a very early congregation in Lincoln, dating to the 1870s, but their present church at 12th and H Streets is exemplary of mid-20th century architecture, not their earlier origins. The use of this early house as a parsonage recalls Trinity’s very long tenure in the heart of the city.

properties.Name: Gamma Phi Beta Sorority
properties.ShortDescription: This three-story sorority house, designed by Kemyss L. Bonebright, a draftsman for Davis & Wilson, is perhaps the best example in UNL’s Greek Row of the Federal Revival style. Built in 1927 the symmetrical facade, central entrance with portico, and Palladian window are all characteristic of the style, as is the Flemish bond brickwork. The house is located at a vital link between the chapter houses on R Street and those on 16th Street, the two streets that became the historic border of City Campus when the fraternities and sororities were built there in the 1910s and ‘20s. Major rear (west) additions were made in 1961 and 1965.

properties.Name: Lewis-Syford House
properties.ShortDescription: The Lewis-Syford House is highly unusual in Lincoln for its University location, very early date of construction, and architectural style. Rev. Elisha M. Lewis, a “home missionary” of the Presbyterian Church, built his house around 1878 in a residential neighborhood when the University of Nebraska campus occupied only the area between R and T Streets from 10th to 12th. In the early 20th century the Syford family began their six decades of occupancy of the house, during which University expansion in the 1910s and ‘20s transformed their surroundings into “Greek Row.”  This very long period of ownership by one family followed by five more decades in possession of the Nebraska State Historical Society Foundation preserved one of Lincoln’s half-dozen residences of the 1860s and ‘70s and a locally rare example of the French Second Empire style. It features a characteristic mansard roof with elaborate dormers and iron cresting. While a relatively small house, its ornate porches and several bay windows add further complexity and interest.
