The property benefits by the careful stewardship of its private owners and the protection of a special preservation provision in its deed.

properties.Name: Phi Kappa Psi Fraternity
properties.ShortDescription: In 1917 Phi Kappa Psi Fraternity house inaugurated the pattern of constructing substantial masonry buildings for fraternities and sororities on the south and east boundaries of the expanding University of Nebraska campus, which became the historic Greek Row district. The Phi Kappa Psi house, designed by A. H. Welch of Columbia, Missouri, is also a clear example of the Federal Revival style.

properties.Name: Sigma Chi Fraternity
properties.ShortDescription: Sigma Chi Fraternity house of 1931 is an exemplary Tudor Revival design by the leading Lincoln architects Davis & Wilson. An addition on the east side nearly doubled the length of the original building along Vine Street with admirable sensitivity.

properties.Name: Foster (John & Mary) House
properties.ShortDescription: The Foster House was under construction by 1881, making it a locally early example of the Queen Anne style that dominated residential construction during Lincoln's booming 1880s. John and Mary Foster were a young farming family when they built the house. They occupied it only briefly. The decorative shinglework, complex massing and rooflines, and varied windows with ample use of colored glass are all typical of the Queen Anne style. The porch was altered after 1903 (probably ca. 1910), adding a favorite feature of the American Foursquare homes of that period.

properties.Name: Slattery (William & Lillian) House
properties.ShortDescription: The Slattery House is one of Lincoln’s best examples of a “country” house, built for a city dweller near but outside the urban area. William Jennings Bryan’s Fairview and Dr. Faulkner’s mansion at 40th and South are other, earlier examples of this type. Dr. Slattery, a leader in the local medical community, chose Fiske & Meginnis, one of Lincoln’s premier architectural partnerships to design his Tudor house on “high and sightly” land north of the then-developed city. Slattery’s land encompassed several hundred acres while the 6.1 acre landmark site is now a very large urban house lot and still provides an appropriate setting.

properties.Name: Standard Oil Company Barn & Garage
properties.ShortDescription: The Standard Oil Company Barn & Garage is a rare remnant of the early automotive era, when horse power and horsepower overlapped. The structure was built in 1915 to accommodate both the trucks and horses or mules that delivered Standard Oil products to dealers and retailers. The second-story portion was originally built as the hay loft. The building’s location beside the railroad reflects yet another key means of transportation in this distribution network. Joseph W. Salmon designed the building which F. P. Gould & Son constructed.

properties.Name: Weese (Hanson & Mattie) Farmstead
properties.ShortDescription: Hanson and Mattie Weese sold a farm northwest of Lincoln in 1917 and purchased property east of Lincoln at 112th and Adams.  They moved to the land in 1918 and built a new house in 1923, using the lumber from the old house to construct a garage.  They had a mixed operation with cattle, hogs, chickens and grain, along with a garden and orchard. The Weeses sold their farm equipment in 1972 and the 160 acre site was donated (with conditions) to the Nebraska State Historical Society Foundation around 1984.  The landmark designation of Weese Farmstead celebrates a characteristic diversified farmstead of early 20th century Lancaster County.

properties.Name: Northeast Branch Library (Matt Talbot Kitchen & Outreach)
properties.ShortDescription: The Northeast Branch “Carnegie” Library is an excellent example of Neo-Classical architecture, designed by German-born George A. Berlinghof. It was built in 1908 as the City of Lincoln’s second Carnegie-funded library. It served as a City branch library until 1982. In 1992, through efforts of the City and neighborhood, it was preserved by relocation from 27th and Orchard to just north of 27th and Fair. In 2008 ownership transferred to Matt Talbot Kitchen & Outreach which added a major addition north and west, designed by Sinclair Hille Architects.

properties.Name: Reimers (Emily) Bungalow
properties.ShortDescription: The Reimers Bungalow demonstrates a new building material—concrete block—in a stylish bungalow designed in 1913 by one of Lincoln’s premier architectural partnerships, Fiske & Miller. Builder W. G. Fullagar was also prominent and prolific, here building for Mrs. Fred Reimers of the Reimers Kauffman concrete company.

properties.Name: Tuttle-Schaupp House
properties.ShortDescription: Tuttle-Schaupp House is a large American Foursquare residence, built in 1902 on land subdivided by Samuel J. Tuttle, an early settler and pioneering attorney in Lincoln whose mansion stood in the center of this block. Emma and Adam Schaupp built and occupied their home for a dozen years. Mr. Schaupp was a coal dealer. The house was extensively renovated in 2010-11 and operates as a commercial property under a special permit for historic preservation.

properties.Name: Ricketts (Arnott & Louisa) Mansion
properties.ShortDescription: The Ricketts House of 1890 exemplifies a very substantial “country” house built by the Harrison Brothers on a large lot near but outside the urbanized area of Lincoln in the 19th century. It commands an elevated site overlooking the city and the Capitol, across the “Rogers Tract” which became Woods Park in the 1950s. The house and site reflect original owner Arnott Rickett’s social and professional standing. He served as City Attorney and several terms on the Lincoln School Board.

properties.Name: Griswold (Robert & Mary) House
properties.ShortDescription: The Griswold House is a well-maintained, locally uncommon example of a French Eclectic style house, built for a prominent Lincoln businessman and his family by Fritz Craig, a prolific local residential architect. It utilizes its large lot to great effect, manifesting the Piedmont ideal of large houses centered in sweeping lawns. It was built in 1935 by Frank A. Robey for Robert Southgate Griswold, Jr. who managed the landscape department of his cousin Wallace Butler Griswold’s seed company which later reorganized as Robert S. Griswold Seed and Floral Company. Their reinforced concrete warehouse and seed elevator still stands at 8th and N Streets.

properties.Name: Zimmer (Jacob & Margaret) Grocery & House
properties.ShortDescription: Small neighborhood grocery stores were common throughout early 20th century Lincoln. The 1908 Lincoln City Directory lists 121 grocers and by 1920 there were nearly 200. Some were solely commercial buildings, others included a second floor residence for the grocer. The Zimmer Grocery store at 1941-43 K Street is an unusual example as the house and store are joined but are distinct units. The house was built first around 1904; the grocery was added in 1906. Jacob L. Zimmer and his family were the original occupants and operators. The store continued into the 1910s and Lincoln Home Bakery used the building in 1920. The landmark designation and accompanying special permit in 2005 allow the current mix of residential and office use.

properties.Name: Charlton (William & Mary) House
properties.ShortDescription: Now used as the Prairie Hill Learning Center, this Italianate-style farmhouse was designed in 1872 by early Lincoln architect Artemas Roberts for William H. Charlton, who came from Illinois to establish a substantial farm in southern Lancaster County. His wife Mary died in 1877 at the age of 25 and is memorialized with a large marble monument at Centerville Cemetery.

properties.Name: Park Hill (Faulkner House)
properties.ShortDescription: Park Hill is an outstanding early example of the Colonial Revival style, built in 1896 for Louis Young and attributed to the architectural partnership of Roberts & Woods , who also designed 'Fairview' for William Jennings Bryan in 1902. Like Fairview, the asymmetry and rich ornament of this large house is reminiscent of the popular Queen Anne style but the detailing of the decoration draws upon Colonial sources. The house stands on a unique 3.4 acre lot, featuring a tree-lined central road originally leading from South Street up the hill to the mansion. Dr. A. O. Faulkner, founder of Woodmen Accident Company (now Assurity Life Insurance Company), occupied the house with his family from about 1900 until his death in 1927.

properties.Name: Hac Grocery (The Chimes)
properties.ShortDescription: The Hac Grocery is a very fine example of a neighborhood grocery store built with the owners’ home above. John H. Nichols built the store and residence for Peter and Carrie Hac in 1916. Their grocery store operated until the 1950s, then their daughter Marguerite Hac offered music lessons in the building which she called “The Chimes.” The broad front stairs lead to an ornate doorway partially hidden by the recessed entryway.

properties.Name: Saint James Lutheran Church
properties.ShortDescription: The former Saint James Evangelical Lutheran Church is among the smallest historic church buildings extant in Lincoln and demonstrates a church with pastor's residence, integrated in a residential area. It was continuously used as a church for approximately 85 years. The church was built in 1925 by W. F. Wagner. It was converted from church use to a duplex after its landmark designation in 2011.

properties.Name: Stevens Creek Stock Farm (Retzlaff Farmstead)
properties.ShortDescription: Located in the picturesque Stevens Creek valley near Lincoln, the farmstead includes nineteen separate structures arranged in a courtyard fashion. The original homestead was acquired in 1858 by Charles and Dora Retzlaff, natives of Germany, and expanded in 1861 and 1873. The farm operation has grown and prospered through multiple generations of the Retzlaff family. Major buildings of the farmstead include the Retzlaff house, a one-and-one-half-story limestone structure built in 1867; and the horse barn, an impressive structure dating from 1901.

properties.Name: Peterson (Peter & Christina) Farmstead
properties.ShortDescription: The Peterson farmstead stands as a significant and well preserved example of Queen Anne architecture somewhat unique in rural Nebraska architecture and specifically important to the local Swedish agricultural community. Most of the structures date from the period 1893 to 1900. The house with a corner tower, echoed in the twin cupolas of the barn, creates an especially picturesque farmstead. Peter Peterson was born in 1838 in Smaland, Sweden. He immigrated to the United States in 1868 and married Christina Olson in 1872 at Nebraska City. She was also a Swede. They soon moved to Lincoln where he worked, presumably as a farm laborer. In 1879 they moved their family to a farm in the Swedeburg settlement, just one quarter mile east of what was then called the “Swede highway.” There they built up this substantial farmstead for which Peter and Christina are credited with the agricultural advancement of the community.

properties.Name: Reynolds (Otero & Nannie) House
properties.ShortDescription: Dr. O. C. Reynolds had D. B. Howard construct this large American Foursquare house in 1905. They used what a contemporary newspaper called “the new building material” – concrete block. This early use of what became a common material employs an alternating pattern of wide and narrow blocks to establish a rich exterior wall texture. Dr. O. C. Reynolds (1857-1911) was a prominent Lincoln physician and surgeon who trained at Louisville (KY) Medical College and St. Louis University.  He practiced in Seward, NE for sixteen years before coming to Lincoln around 1895.  At the time of his death he was president of the medical staff at St. Elizabeth Hospital, then Lincoln’s only general hospital.

properties.Name: Wheeler (Myron & Cora) House
properties.ShortDescription: Myron Wheeler’s house of 1891 is an excellent example of the Queen Anne style with its richly varied shinglework, complex massing and rooflines, and varied windows. Wheeler was recognized as a leader in the unglamorous but highly responsible and necessary field of court reporting, serving in various courts for over 50 years before his death in 1937. Its remodeled porch of the early 20th century aligns stylistically with its American Foursquare neighbors.

properties.Name: Kirkwood Brothel (Mission Arts)
properties.ShortDescription: By the 1880s through the beginning of the 20th century, a frame house at this site was used as a brothel, for many years owned by a prominent madam named Lydia Stewart. Prostitution was outlawed in Lincoln by 1885 but was tacitly tolerated in the nineteenth and early twentieth centuries, especially in the so-called "Burnt District" west of 9th Street, generally between P and J Streets. After Stewart's death in 1893, Rose Kirkwood operated the house, and in 1903 she built the two-story brick brothel, just around the corner from Government Square.  In addition to the front door centered on the west façade, a more discreet entrance was provided via the passageway on the south. In the early 20th century, reform-minded Lincolnites organized People's City Mission to serve needy residents, especially new immigrants.  The group purchased Kirkwood's building by 1910 for the dual purpose of eliminating the house of prostitution, and to establish a downtown Mission.  In 1929 People's City Mission doubled the size of their building with an addition to the east.  The building continued as the City Mission through 1987, when a new, larger facility was constructed at 1st and Q Streets. Judith Andre rehabilitated 124 South 9th as Mission Arts, providing galleries, artists' studios, and two apartments.

properties.Name: Meadow Gold Complex
properties.Builder: Varous: P.H. Bush, W.J. Assenmacher Co.
properties.ShortDescription: The Meadow Gold Block consists of a dozen buildings occupying a full city block built between 1902 and 1916. The earliest buildings on the south half of the block originally housed a local ice and cold storage company. Beatrice Creamery Company had its origins a few blocks north in Lincoln’s wholesale district (now called Haymarket), incorporating in 1898 by George Haskell. The Meadow Gold Block exemplifies that company’s meteoric expansion in the early 20th century based on innovations in transportation and collection of raw material, processing, packaging, and marketing. Architecturally, although buildings were built by several different enterprises, under Beatrice’s management a high degree of design coordination was achieved.

properties.Name: Sigma Alpha Epsilon Fraternity
properties.ShortDescription: The Sigma Alpha Epsilon Fraternity house of 1927 is an excellent example of the Tudor style applied to a fraternity chapter house. It is the most decorative of Miller & Craig's ten Greek house designs at the University of Nebraska with a noteworthy entrance pavilion under ornately carved barge boards and richly textured brickwork.

properties.Name: Lincoln Air Force Base (LAFB) Remote Facility
properties.ShortDescription: This small complex of buildings was constructed circa 1955 by the U. S. Government as a communication component of the nearby Lincoln Air Force Base. Its location contributes to the interpretation and understanding of Lincoln’s significant role in the early years of the Cold War.

properties.Name: Schaaf (Conrad & Theresa) House
properties.ShortDescription: C. A. Schaaf was a prolific builder of very substantial houses throughout the central neighborhoods of Lincoln, both on his own account and for architects such as Ferdinand C. Fiske. Schaaf also established a millwork factory. He built this substantial bungalow in 1920 for his own family. It demonstrates his competence as a designer and the interior retains products of his millwork factory.

properties.Name: Bowman-Cameron House
properties.ShortDescription: The two story Italianate house with a prominent Neo-Classical front porch was built circa 1885 by Thomas P. Harrison, a local carpenter/contractor, for Dr. John W. and Catherine Bowman. Dr. Bowman was treasurer of Lincoln Insurance Company and later served as superintendent of the Lincoln Hospital for the Insane. Among the long term residents were Joseph and Mable Cameron. Mr. Cameron was the County Commissioner in the 3rd District from 1919 until 1935, the longest term held by anyone in county office at the time.

properties.Name: Municipal Pool Bath House (Muny Building)
properties.ShortDescription: The Fiske & Meginnis Muny Building of 1921 has Spanish Colonial Revival features and is significant as an early example of Lincoln's substantial commitment to parks and outdoor recreation and to dignified civic architecture. It also gained significance as the site of long, persistent, ultimately successful struggle for equal access to community facilities for all residents. The leadership of Rev. Trago T. McWilliams and his son, Rev. Trago O. McWilliams, in civil rights activities spanning several decades is a significant chapter in Lincoln’s heritage.

properties.Name: O'Connell-Galbraith House
properties.ShortDescription: This house was built around 1881 for John O’Connell and is among the oldest surviving brick houses in Lincoln. While altered, it still retains its essential early form. It was subsequently occupied by people of Irish, African, and German ancestry which is highly characteristic of the pattern of this “port of entry” neighborhood. In the mid-teens this was the home of John and Mabel Galbraith, who were photographed in front of the house by African-American photographer John Johnson.  The rare survival of the residential setting of several John Johnson photographs lends special interest and significance to this small house.

properties.Name: Wesleyan Hospital
properties.ShortDescription: When built in 1906 the east portion of this building was a small hotel, Hotel Cecil, and the west front was Dr. Coffin’s private hospital called Wesleyan Hospital and Nurses Training School. The hospital and school quickly expanded into the hotel, but the school only operated until 1912. Its uses alternated in the 1910s between a boarding house and hospital, then was converted into apartments in the 1920s.  In 2016-17 it was rehabbed for a dozen apartments.

properties.Name: Rees (David & Anna) House
properties.ShortDescription: The Rees House is one of the very small number of Art Moderne houses constructed in Lincoln. The architectural significance of the house is heightened by its prominent corner site, excellent design integrity, and stylistic clarity. The building permit of 1938 lists Professor David D. Rees, manager of Christian Record braille publishing house, as the contractor on behalf of Central Conference (Seventh-day Adventist). Anna Rees was the librarian for Christian Record.

properties.Name: Betz/VanAndel Houses
properties.ShortDescription: The Betz and VanAndel Houses are an exemplary pair of American Foursquare residences built in 1912 on a single lot at the prominent intersection of 13th and D Streets. They demonstrate the turn-of-the-century intensification of Lincoln's Everett neighborhood.

properties.Name: Koop (Amel & Martha) House
properties.ShortDescription: German-born architect George A. Berlinghof of Lincoln designed this unique residence in 1915, combining elements of bungalows and period revival homes. This type of composition in the hands of a well-trained and experienced architect comprises a style referred to as Academic Eclecticism. We also see it in the work of Ferdinand C. Fiske, for instance at the nearby Funk House, 1601 A Street. Berlinghof’s client, Amel H. Koop, was a downtown retailer. His house is particularly well located opposite the south end of wide Goodhue Boulevard. The ample living room windows take advantage of the view north up the boulevard to the Capitol.

properties.Name: Sheldon Musium of Art
properties.ShortDescription: The Sheldon Museum of Art and its associated sculpture garden were designed by the renowned architect Philip Johnson and built in 1963, reflecting the era of Modern architecture with New Formalism styling. The museum houses more than 12,000 works of American Art and sculpture attained through the University of Nebraska Art collection as well as the collection of the Hayden Art Club, founded in 1888 (now Sheldon Art Association).

properties.Name: Sky Park Manor
properties.ShortDescription: Sky Park Manor is a twelve-story, high-rise, luxury apartment building completed in 1963 in the International style. Sky Park is the tallest structure in the immediate vicinity of the Capitol, and was built before the modern Capitol Environs height limits were in place. Designed by Selmer A. Solheim and built by Olson Construction, the building provided two penthouse apartments for the building’s developers—Selmer Solheim and Carl Olson.

properties.Name: Antelope Park Zoo Aviary (Ager Building)
properties.ShortDescription: The Zoo Aviary Building, commonly known as the Ager Building, was a year-round zoo facility of the Depression era, operating from 1938 to the 1970s. The limestone structure was designed by Davis & Wilson and constructed in 1936-38 as a project of the federal Works Progress Administration (WPA). This zoo project could have only been accomplished through the WPA, for the availability of money was scarce, but the availability of laborers was enormous. Park administrators had to be very frugal and creative with their resources. Examples of this frugality include recycling materials. Most of the limestone was quarried by city crews in Roca, south of Lincoln and nearly all of the lumber used in the building was milled from dead trees removed from city parks. The interior was altered to provide an indoor playground in the 1990s, however in 2017 the building became part of the Children’s Zoo expansion returning it to its original use as an indoor zoo facility.

properties.Name: Cordner (John & Adella) House
properties.ShortDescription: The landmark designation protects a locally rare example of a large, cross-gambrel Dutch Colonial Revival house, designed, built circa 1911-1914 and long-occupied by Lincoln architect John G. Cordner. The family originally had a ten-acre house site, encompassing the whole area bounded by L, M, 54th and 56th Streets. The house was oriented toward 56th Street. Cordner and his family had orchards and raised poultry on their acreage. Family remained in ownership until 1948. The next owners created 30 additional house lots which were soon developed with the houses that surround the original Cordner House. In 2016 the Langer family acquired the house for their own residence and to develop a “pocket neighborhood” in the heart of the block.

properties.Name: First German Congregational Church
properties.ShortDescription: Both North and South Bottoms were Lincoln neighborhoods settled by Germans from Russia in the late 19th and early 20th centuries. Both are dotted with churches, which were a central part of community life. A. W. Woods designed half of these churches and First German Congregational (now First Street Bible Church) is a well-preserved example of his work, serving Lincoln’s predominant early immigrant group. This church was built in 1920 by George Schumackar and is a contributing property in the South Bottoms Historic District.

properties.Name: Hawley District
properties.ShortDescription: The district derives its name from Allen W. Hawley, who platted Hawley's Addition in June of 1884, during Lincoln's "boom" decade of growth.  The district had approximately a forty-six-year period of development (1884-1930).  The variety of architectural styles, the long list of distinguished Lincoln citizens who made this neighborhood their home, the district's ties to events that shaped the City of Lincoln, as well as its many links to commerce and the university all contribute to the importance of the Hawley District to the City of Lincoln.

properties.Name: Haymarket District
properties.ShortDescription:
Haymarket Landmark District was federally certified as the equivalent of a National Register District in 1984.  Development of the area was shaped by the entry of Burlington and Missouri River Railroad into Lincoln in 1870, with the first group of wood-frame depot buildings located around 5th and Q Streets in the Salt Creek floodplain.  The higher ground to the east became Lincoln's prime  location  for wholesale houses (especially groceries), farm implement manufactures and dealers, and other businesses (such as hotels and cafes) reliant upon rail passengers and freight service.  Several buildings remain from the 1880s and 1890s, most of the rest were built between 1900 and the construction of the current depot (Lincoln Station) in 1927.
The area retains a high degree of integrity of historic structures as well as displaying sensitive rehabilitions carried out since revitalization efforts began in the last quarter of the 20th century.  8th Street is lined with loading docks, many now serving as outdoor dining areas.  7th Street is dominated by the Depot and is brick-paved from P to Q Streets, as are several of the alleys.  The t-shaped alley between 8th and 9th, south of  O and extending to N, is Lincoln's only paving-stone alley.

properties.Name: East Lincoln / Elm Park District
properties.ShortDescription: The East Lincoln/Elm Park District consists of the majority of two plats—the East Lincoln Addition of 1868 and the Elm Park Addition of 1905. Despite the very early date of “East Lincoln,” a large majority of the houses on both plats were built between 1905 and 1920. A few late-19th century houses can be found in the East Lincoln Plat, along with a few mid-20th century “intrusions” scattered throughout the area, and a single church at 29th and Randolph, built in 1918.

properties.Name: Woods Park Bungalow District
properties.ShortDescription: The Woods Park Bungalow District is Lincoln’s best existing example of an early 20th century “starter home” neighborhood. Its high concentration of 1- to 1 1/2-story bungalows on small lots is typical of single-family American vernacular architecture during the period of 1910 to 1930. Its integrity is largely intact, as is the charm of its pervasive Craftsman style. This neighborhood exhibits some of the best work of prominent Lincoln builders, including Edward A. Gehrke (“the Bungalow Man”), Star Realty Company, and Ludwig H. Pauley. As a cultural landmark, it represents an important milestone in the American middle-class dream of home ownership.

properties.Name: Clark-Leonard District
properties.ShortDescription: The Clark-Leonard Landmark District has some of Lincoln’s finest Queen Anne style homes in addition to several residences that enhance the Clark-Leonard Mansion’s monumentality. Early residents of the district contributed to commerce and education in Lincoln. The Clark-Leonard mansion, located at 1937 F Street, is a brick and stone Queen Anne residence built in 1887. John R. Clark, a leading banker and businessman, had the home built, while William M. Leonard was a later owner who also worked in banking, investment, and life insurance.

properties.Name: Mount Emerald District
properties.ShortDescription: John Fitzgerald, an Irish immigrant and probably Lincoln’s first millionaire, acquired 10 acres on the hilltop east of 19th and north of A Street and built Mount Emerald—his mansion—in 1880. Then in 1904 when Fitzgerald’s land became available, over 50 houses were quickly built where his mansion had stood. From the time the area began developing through the 1930’s, the Mount Emerald Addition and surrounding areas were home to Lincoln’s wealthiest residents who contributing to Nebraska’s development in the fields of education, government, and insurance, and banking. One of the most prominent buildings in the district is the First Plymouth Congregation Church, a Lincoln landmark dedicated in 1931.

properties.Name: Capitol Addition District
properties.ShortDescription: When Lincoln was platted in 1867, 17th Street was the eastern boundary. Property owners of adjacent land optimistically began platting their land as well leading to the Capitol Addition in 1870 between 17th and 19th Streets. The district has a significant concentration of homes built in the late 1800’s and early 1900’s. Two highly notable Lincoln residences in the district include the Weil House and McAfee House. The Morris Weil House is a two and a half story Georgian Revival/Neo-Classical home built in 1902-03. The McAfee House was designed by architect Paul V. Hyland for Boston interior decorator James L. McAfee in 1916. The district was also home to Charles Bryan, Governor of Nebraska and a former Lincoln mayor.

properties.Name: Hillsdale District
properties.ShortDescription: The Hillsdale Addition, bounded by 20th, 24th, A and D Streets, was subdivided in 1886. The district is also known as the Sidles-Rogers-Grainger-Walts district for the prominent early residents. The district has a notable collection of early 20th century residences representing distinctive architectural styles, primarily the Jacobethan Revival and the Prairie School. The district is associated with persons who made a significant commercial contribution to Lincoln’s heritage.

properties.Name: Franklin Heights District
properties.ShortDescription: The Franklin Heights Addition was platted on the far southeast edge of Lincoln in 1889 by two Pennsylvania couples, the Seals and the Peppers.  The plat of approximately 25 acres is bounded by Sumner Street on the north, 27th Street on the east, South Street on the south, and 24th and 25th Streets on the west.  Little of the land was sold before Mark and George Woods and Charles Boggs bought out the original investors in the early 1900s. They replatted some of the original blocks so that all the house lots faced the north-south streets and began promoting the addition as "the most beautiful residence district in the City of Lincoln."  Within three years they had sold 130 of their "high and sightly" lots, "the right direction out from the city."  A fascinating mix of houses was built here from 1906 through the 1920s, ranging from small bungalows to mansions, joining the few earlier houses already in place.  Mature landscaping, well-maintained houses, a stretch of brick-paved street, and a scarcity of intrusive newer buildings combine to form a cohesive district that bears out the Woods Brothers' early advertisements.

properties.Name: Greek Row District
properties.ShortDescription: "Greek Row" is adjacent the City Campus of the University of Nebraska-Lincoln. These fraternity and sorority houses were not just residences, but an environment that promoted character and social position for many young college students. The clustering of the houses in the 1910s and ‘20s was the result of many factors, which include the expansion of the City Campus due to the doubling of enrollment, the adoption of a master plan for university expansion (the Seymour Plan), and the university's hesitancy in providing student dormitories.

properties.Name: East Campus Neighborhood District
properties.ShortDescription: The East Campus Neighborhood Landmark District, sometimes called “Professors Row,” is a premier residential area, developed by the Woods Bros., Henry C. Luckey, Howard R. Smith, and others in the early 20th century.  Many of the early and longtime residents of the area were professors, deans, and other staff associated with agricultural research and education at the University of Nebraska’s nearby Experimental Farm/Agriculture Campus/East Campus. The houses of the area display a wide range of sizes and diverse residential styles from the first half of the 20th century including American Foursquares (“Prairie Boxes”), bungalows, Period Revival homes (e.g. Colonial, Tudor, and Dutch Colonial), and post-World War II ranch houses. The landscape of the area is enhanced by the long blocks from Holdrege to Apple and their distinctive cast-iron streetlights, along with mature trees and hedges.  The old Interurban Railroad right-of-way remains a strong feature, providing a pedestrian link at the heart of the area.

properties.Name: South Bottoms District
properties.ShortDescription: South Bottoms is a predominantly residential area with Lincoln’s original park, a middle school, and many churches, located in the bottomlands of Salt Creek. Built and occupied largely by Germans from Russia who emigrated from the Volga River region to this area in the late 19th and early 20th centuries, the district occupies approximately seventy-four square blocks with over 1,000 properties. The neighborhood was also home to many of Lincoln’s African American residents. The largest and probably the most distinct urban ethnic neighborhood in the state, the South Bottoms exemplifies the importance of immigrants in settling the cities and towns of the Great Plains. The international headquarters of the American Historical Society of Germans from Russia is located at 6th and D Streets.

properties.Name: Everett District
properties.ShortDescription:
Everett Landmark District features Lincoln's most diverse collection of historic residences, along with historic Everett School (1928) at 11th & C, for which the district and surrounding neighorhood are named.  The John Miller House at 1029 E (1874) and Cullen House at 905 E (ca. 1873) are among the earliest residences in the city.  Albert Watkins House (920 D St.) and  Outcalt-Hall House (1039 S. 11th) are outstanding examples of Queen Anne style residences.  Barr Terrace (NW corner of 11th & H) and Lyman Terrace (SE corner of 11th & H) are the sole surviving row houses of Lincoln's booming 1880s. Early apartment houses such as The Lorraine (712 S. 11th), Apollo (730 S. 11th), LaBelle (740 S. 11th), and Mariposa  (745 S. 12th) demonstrate the multi-family housing which flourished in the mid-1910s.
The extra-wide (120') right-of-way of S. 11th Street forms the central spine of the district.  This featuresdates to the 1867 Original Plat of Lincoln, which designated certain wider streets to create vistas to the major sites of the plan.  11th St. led to the center of the original University of Nebraska campus and the original Nebraska Hall.

properties.Name: Havelock Avenue District
properties.ShortDescription: Havelock Avenue, first called Jackson Avenue and later (1912-1930) called “O” Street in the town of Havelock, was the main commercial district of the independent town of Havelock from its incorporation in 1893 to its annexation in 1930. It retains the scale, architectural character, and many of the buildings of that period. The nearly continuous streetscape of one and two story, flat roofed commercial buildings, flanking wide sidewalks and the two-way street with on-street parking, retains the appearance of a typical small-town “Main Street.” The Lancaster Block at 62nd and Havelock on the east and the Joyo Theater, Schmidt building, and Masonic Temple building near 61st and Havelock on the west “bookend” the district.

properties.Name: Creighton (Charles F.) District
properties.ShortDescription: In the late 1880s and early 1890s, six institutions of higher learning were established on the outskirts of Lincoln, with residential land platted around the campuses in hopes of establishing independent “college towns.” Nebraska Wesleyan University and its surrounding University Place along with Union College and College View are Lincoln’s most successful examples of this form of development. The University Place District demonstrates the residential component of this phenomenon and displays a range of homes including Prairie Boxes, bungalows, and a few modest Period Revival houses.

properties.Name: Boulevards District
properties.ShortDescription: This large residential district contains over 1,200 historic properties, including houses, brick streets, and religious and public buildings. The area’s distinctive landscape features were designed by Jens Jensen, a nationally prominent landscape architect, and by Ernst Herminghaus, a native Lincolnite who was Nebraska's first academically trained landscape architect. The winding boulevards and streets conceived of by the Woods Brothers beginning in 1909 were the first to deviate from Lincoln's original grid pattern. The distinctive neighborhood they created influenced Lincoln’s city planning for years to come. The houses in the district range from Period Revival mansions to modest bungalows and Ranch style houses, built as the area developed over the first half of the 20th century.

properties.Name: Woodsshire District
properties.ShortDescription: Located in south central Lincoln, and developed with 131 single-family residences, Woodsshire is a 40-acre subdivision of 1926, designed by Nebraska's first academically trained landscape architect, Ernst Herminghaus. Woodsshire was platted with a modified grid of streets, limited entry points, landscaped traffic circles or “Round Points” at four of the intersections, and a private park along a drainage at the west side of the area, oriented towards the Nebraska State Capitol tower, two miles distant. Many of the district's Period Revival style homes showcase the work of Lincoln's leading residential architects.

properties.Name: Mount Emerald & Capitol Additions District
properties.ShortDescription:
The Mount Emerald & Capitol Additions National Register District stretches from 17th & G to 22nd & A. Within its boundaries are four Lincoln Landmark Districts (Mount Emerald, Capitol Addition, Hillsdale, and Clark-Leonard). The historic district comprises twenty blocks with 228 residential and religious structures dating from the late nineteenth and early twentieth centuries. 

When Lincoln was platted in 1867, 17th Street was the eastern boundary. Property owners of adjacent land optimistically began platting their land as well. Capitol Addition was platted in 1870 between 17th and 19th Streets. The oldest houses in this portion of the district date from the 1880s and include notable residences such as the R. 0. Phillips House, an impressive Richardsonian Romanesque dwelling, and the James Wampler House, a fine product of Italianate design. 

John Fitzgerald, an Irish immigrant and probably Lincoln’s first millionaire, acquired 10 acres on the hilltop east of 19th and north of A Street and built Mount Emerald—his mansion—in 1880. The city continued growing beyond his site as Hillsdale Addition was subdivided in 1886 bounded by 20th, 24th, A and D Streets. Then in 1904 when Fitzgerald’s houselot became available over 50 houses were quickly built where his mansion had stood in the Mount Emerald Addition. The most substantial building in the district is the First Plymouth Congregational Church, a Lincoln landmark dedicated in 1931. The Mount Emerald and Capitol Additions area of Lincoln was a middle- and upper-middle-class residential neighborhood, whose residents reflected the governmental, educational, and commercial character of the growing city.

properties.Name: Brownbilt District
properties.ShortDescription: Brownbilt District in central Lincoln is a 47-acre neighborhood platted in several subdivisions between 1925 and 1946. The District's significance derives from its very strong concentration of residences financed by the newly created Federal Housing Administration (FHA). FHA was the New Deal's response to a near-cessation of housing construction during the Great Depression. Of note was FHA's explicit support of racial segregation in its lending policies, resulting in Brownbilt's racially restrictive covenants. Brownbilt is also locally significant as an exemplary collection of smaller residences of the 1930s and '40s, with a large majority constructed by a single contractor, Howard A. Brown.

properties.Name: Park Manor District
properties.ShortDescription: Park Manor was on the outskirts of Lincoln until after World War II, when new suburban neighborhoods began to be created. They were characterized by wide, winding streets with few connections to arterials and by uniformity of house designs and lot layouts. Peterson Construction platted Park Manor and designed and built the majority of the houses in the neighborhood. While they sold some lots to other builders, Peterson Construction retained the final approval of all house designs, producing considerable continuity within the neighborhood. As mid-20th century houses gain the attention of historians and homebuyers alike, variations within the Ranch style can be categorized and students of the style can find the full range in Park Manor.

properties.Name: Veterans Administration Hospital
properties.ShortDescription: The Lincoln Veterans Administration (VA) Hospital Historic District encompasses the remaining 57 acres of the 300-plus acre Leavitt farm that formed the original hospital campus.  The major buildings remain, constructed of red brick and buff terra cotta, arrayed along an arc facing the wide front lawn. The VA Hospital District is significant architecturally and historically, demonstrating the nation’s commitment to the care not only of veterans of World War I, but also of WWII and subsequent periods of service.

properties.Name: Leavitt (Bert & Faythe) House
properties.ShortDescription: The Leavitt House is a concrete block, American Foursquare-style farmhouse built for the Bert Leavitt family on the southeast corner of 70th and O Streets around 1912. The adjacent farm, along with the house, was sold to the U. S. Government in 1929 and the Lincoln VA Hospital was developed on that site. The medical center used the house for decades, then declared it surplus in the 1980s. The house was evaluated as eligible for listing on the National Register of Historic places and when it was sold in the 1990s, covenants were placed on it requiring review by the Historical Society of redevelopment plans. The Society approved the relocation of the house to a more rural setting several years ago, in hopes of enhancing its preservation. The Stahr family received the “Stewardship” award of the Preservation Association of Lincoln in 2007 for their relocation and rehabilitation of the Leavitt House.

properties.Name: Agricultural Hall (Industrial Arts Building)
properties.ShortDescription: Agriculture Hall, now the Industrial Arts Building in Lincoln, is a distinctively shaped, trapezoidal building on the south edge of the former State Fairgrounds, now Nebraska Innovation Campus. Architect Burd F. Miller of Omaha was hired to design the building which was built in 1913. Integral to the original structure was the post-and-truss system of the interior open space, which featured the same trapezoidal shape as the building. Additionally, the building represents facility growth during the State Fair's expansion period. Before the building’s integration into Innovation Campus, it was the subject of a preservation debate including listing by the National Trust as a “Most Endangered Property.” The red brick arcaded walls with bold white decorative keystones still make a strong statement at the primary entrance to the campus.

properties.Name: Herter (Abraham & Catherine) Farmstead
properties.ShortDescription: The Herter Farmstead is located on a parcel of 120 acres, bounded by Pioneers on the north and 148th on the east, in the agricultural area east of Lincoln. Its operations began in 1876. The farmstead is a rare and well-preserved collection of nine agricultural buildings that reflect farming in Nebraska in the late 19th and early 20th centuries. The Herter House is a good example of a vernacular interpretation of the Queen Anne, free classical style.

properties.Name: Nebraska Governor's Mansion
properties.ShortDescription: Nebraska’s Governor’s Mansion, built in 1957, replaced a large Neo-Classical Revival residence on the northeast corner of the same block. The earlier house was built in the 1890s for the Thompson family but served as the Governor’s residence for the first half of the 20th century. The current Mansion draws its historical significance from the discussions, even controversy, that attended its creation. The building’s architect Selmer A. Solheim is better known for his Modernist designs, such as the nearby Sky Park apartment tower, but for the Mansion a more conventional Colonial Revival style was selected. The Mansion originally occupied only the north half of the block, but the grounds were ultimately expanded to encompass the whole city block.

properties.Name: Nebraska State Historical Society Building
properties.ShortDescription: Although the Nebraska State Historical Society was founded in 1878, it was not until 1953 that the Society successfully constructed its first purpose-built headquarters. The site on the edge of UNL’s City Campus has special significance in Lincoln’s city plan, serving as the terminus of the north vista from the Capitol. Designed by the firm Davis & Wilson, the building’s form, materials, and style are a sensitive response to the landmark Capitol, 7 blocks away.

properties.Name: Schrader Archeological Site
properties.ShortDescription: Situated on a terrace of Salt Creek about 9 miles south of Lincoln near Roca, the Schrader Site was a late prehistoric community. Pottery and other artifacts retrieved from the locations of three earthlodges link the site to what archeologists term the Smoky Hill Phase (950-1350 CE) of settlements in eastern Kansas and southeast Nebraska.

properties.Name: Trail Ruts at Spring Creek Prairie
properties.ShortDescription: Located at Spring Creek Prairie near Denton in rural Lancaster County these trail ruts are significant to Nebraska's history for their association with the Oregon Trail. From about 1840 through 1866, when the Union Pacific Railroad reached Fort Kearny, the Oregon Trail was the most important transportation corridor for the westward movement of people and supplies. Government freighting contractors and emigrants continually looked for shorter and faster routes from the Missouri River to the Oregon Trail. One such route was the Fort Kearny Cutoff, originating in Nebraska City and traversing this portion of Lancaster County. The several sets of ruts in Spring Creek Prairie demonstrate how the wagons would disperse from a single line to find safe routes down a steep grade in preparation for crossing a creek.

properties.Name: Theta Xi Fraternity
properties.ShortDescription: The Art Deco style of the Theta Xi fraternity house helps anchor the 16th and R street intersection at the heart of the Greek Row Historic District.

properties.Name: Saint Elizabeth Hospital Nurses Home (Trabert Hall)
properties.ShortDescription: The former Nurses Home of Saint Elizabeth Hospital, Trabert Hall is indicative of the scale of the original Saint Elizabeth Hospital complex and is the only original structure of the complex still extant.

properties.Name: Burgess House
properties.ShortDescription: Annie and Joseph Burgess were highly successful both as farmers and in raising a large family in rural Lancaster County. Their American Foursquare farmhouse of 1912 reflects the most popular house-type of that time in this region, but is specifically reflects their prosperity and their large family in its six-bedroom upper story (rather than the typical four bedrooms). It is also distinguished by its very high degree of architectural integrity and ownership by the same family for over a century.

properties.Name: University Place City Hall
properties.ShortDescription: University Place City Hall is the premier architectural representation of the City of University Place during its autonomous period from incorporation in 1889 to annexation by Lincoln in 1926. Built in 1914 in the Neo-Classical Revival style, it embodies the growth of University Place to a community of approximately 5,000 by the time of annexation. Designed to house the fire station, police station, water & light departments, city council, and mayor, it embodies the full range of civic services offered by the community during that period. It is also a major work in the career of John R. Smith, University Place’s leading architect of the independent period.

properties.Name: Strode Building
properties.ShortDescription: The Strode Building is significant as a large, early automotive building, very prominently located downtown, designed by Fiske & Meginnis, one of Lincoln's leading architectural partnerships of the first quarter of the 20th century.

properties.Name: University Place Residential District
properties.ShortDescription: In the late 1880s and early 1890s, six institutions of higher learning were established on the outskirts of Lincoln, with residential land platted around the campuses in hopes of establishing independent “college towns.” Nebraska Wesleyan University and its surrounding University Place along with Union College and College View are Lincoln’s most successful examples of this form of development. The University Place District demonstrates the residential component of this phenomenon and displays a range of homes including Prairie Boxes, bungalows, and a few modest Period Revival houses.

properties.Name: Caplan-Mohr House
properties.ShortDescription: The Caplan House is significant both as a distinctive example of a Tudor Revival style house of the early 1930s, and also for the unusually rich documentary record pf tje suppliers, tradesman, and developers who added to our knowledge of Depression-era housebuilding in Lincoln.

properties.Name: Beeler House
properties.ShortDescription: The Beeler House is a fine example of the Tudor Revival style and a solid contributor to the character of the Woodsshire Residential Historic District.

properties.Name: Cooley-Dodge Farmstead
properties.ShortDescription: The Cooley-Dodge Farmstead consists of a large, modified American Foursquare farmhouse and an ensemble of five outbuildings within a substantial tree mass/windbreak, on a 17 acre site.

properties.Name: Luckey-Pelikan House
properties.ShortDescription: The Luckey-Pelikan House was built by Henry C. Luckey in 1928-29.  This large brick and stucco Tudor Revival residence is the largest built by Luckey in the East Campus residential neighborhood. Long-time residents Dr. Charles C & Elsie Pelikan owned the house for nearly 30 years.

properties.Name: Lincoln Haymarket District
properties.ShortDescription:
Haymarket Landmark District was federally certified as the equivalent of a National Register District in 1984.  Development of the area was shaped by the entry of Burlington and Missouri River Railroad into Lincoln in 1870, with the first group of wood-frame depot buildings located around 5th and Q Streets in the Salt Creek floodplain.  The higher ground to the east became Lincoln's prime  location  for wholesale houses (especially groceries), farm implement manufactures and dealers, and other businesses (such as hotels and cafes) reliant upon rail passengers and freight service.  Several buildings remain from the 1880s and 1890s, most of the rest were built between 1900 and the construction of the current depot (Lincoln Station) in 1927.
The area retains a high degree of integrity of historic structures as well as displaying sensitive rehabilitions carried out since revitalization efforts began in the last quarter of the 20th century.  8th Street is lined with loading docks, many now serving as outdoor dining areas.  7th Street is dominated by the Depot and is brick-paved from P to Q Streets, as are several of the alleys.  The t-shaped alley between 8th and 9th, south of  O and extending to N, is Lincoln's only paving-stone alley.

properties.Name: Eastridge District
properties.ShortDescription: Eastridge neighborhood is significant in the areas of community development and commerce (marketing) and architecture as Lincoln’s largest Cold War neighborhood developed and built by a single firm, with distinct characteristics of its period in layout, construction methods, materials, and style. The period of significance includes the entire space of construction—1953 to 1965—and the significant dates are the platting dates from the original master plan and Eastridge Addition of 1953 and the subsequent platting of Eastridge First Addition (1954) through Eastridge Fifth Addition (1960). There is a religious property in the district, Eastridge Presbyterian Church, which is significant as part of the original master planning and marketing of the neighborhood (not for its specific religious character) but is counted as non-contributing due to major alterations outside of the period of significance.

properties.Name: Basket Store No. 8 (Yakel Grocery)
properties.ShortDescription: Basket Store No. 8/Yakel Grocery reflects the early 20th century pattern of grocery retailing which originally saw approximately 200 small stores operating throughout Lincoln (by 1920), mostly in residential neighborhoods. Only a handful of those buildings still stand, and this is the earliest extant “Basket Store,” representing an early “chain” of stores that eventually operated regionally. As a purpose-built residence-above-store, it also exemplifies a significant type of retail building much more common in predominantly commercial settings but less frequently seen in residential areas.

properties.Name: Robber's Cave
properties.ShortDescription: Robbers’ Cave is a subterranean complex of five primary tunnels carved out of the Dakota sandstone bedrock. The original portion of the cave was a naturally-eroded void that was considerably enlarged and expanded by the Lincoln Brewery from 1869 to 1872 to serve as a production and storage facility for their products. After brewing operations at the site ceased in the late 1870s, the cave transitioned into being a destination for social and recreational gatherings, and it remains in that use to the present day.

properties.Name: Curtis & Bartlett Building
properties.ShortDescription: The Cotswold Building tells the early story of Curtis, Towle & Paine, and it highlights the hardships faced by buildings in the South Haymarket district. In 1894 the firm was housed in three iron-clad buildings at 6th and M Streets. The Curtis companies continued to grow with another branch in Chicago, and by 1902 they claimed to have “the largest factory of its kind in the United States” with 1,200 employees. In 1903 a fire devastated nearly all the structures, except for the brick building to the east that stands today. The Cotswold Building was renovated in 1991, with a second floor added at that time.

properties.Name: Chi Omega House
properties.ShortDescription: Chi Omega is a prominently sited Greek house on the east side of North 16th Street within UNL's Greek Row, which overall constitutes a very distinctive academically related setting in the community. The house is an excellent representative of the several Period Revival chapter houses designed by the prominent Lincoln architects MIller & Craig.

properties.Name: Yates Martin House
properties.ShortDescription: The Yates-Martin House is significant as an excellent example of the Colonial Revival style of architecture. Although there are several other houses of the same style in the district, there is no other of this size, nor of its design quality. It is for those reasons this house is a focal point within the district. In addition to its architectural qualities, the structure was home to two prominent Lincoln residents who impacted the physical and civic development of the community. Willard S Yates, the man who built the home, operated one of Lincoln’s early lumber yards, supplying the material necessary during Lincoln’s early years of growth. The subsequent homeowner, Mr. Bennett S. Martin, was a leading business, civic, and political figure in Lincoln and the state for 50 years.

properties.Name: Epworth Church
properties.ShortDescription: The Epworth Church is architecturally significant in Lincoln as an excellent example of the Late Gothic Revival style of architecture (of which none to date in this style have been designated locally or in the National Register in Lincoln) with a high degree of integrity remaining with the original stained-glass windows and stonework. A unique feature of the building is the double hung stained glass windows designed by architect Jesse B. Miller in 1921. A 1962 addition was completed by the Epworth Church for their education facility. They remained at this location until they merged with Faith United Methodist Church down the street at N. 33rd and Starr Streets, selling the building in 1973.

properties.Name: Iowa Nebraska Light and Power Co
properties.ShortDescription: The K-Street Power Plant was built by the Iowa Nebraska Light and Power Company in 1930. The complex provided power for both the city of Lincoln and surrounding rural areas. It represents the advancements of rural electrification and soon thereafter, public power in Lincoln. The site was home to power equipment from the earliest days of electrification in Lincoln, and in 1930 this building was constructed to house advanced equipment to generate power. Even with multiple owners over time, the site has always been known as the K-Street Power Plant. It is locally significant under Criterion A as a power plant, and the period of significance begins in 1930 when the building was constructed and extends through 1971, when the city purchased the building and the slow shut down began.

properties.Name: First Evangelical Church
properties.ShortDescription: The First Evangelical Church is a two and a half story L-shaped brick structure on the southwest corner of North 33rd and Starr Street. The unique style is reminiscent of the Tudor style with board and batten siding and steep pitched rooflines. The church is significant for its association with the evolution and growth of religious institutions in Lincoln.

properties.Name: Speidel Barn
properties.ShortDescription: The Speidel barn is architecturally significant as one of the few remaining Gothic arch barns, a unique laminated truss system, in Lancaster County given the expansion of the urban growth boundary. The period of significance begins in 1932 with the construction of the barn for William Speidel and ends in 1973, fifty years prior to the date of this nomination, capturing the barn's agricultural and entertainment and recreational use, although 1995 was the last year hay was in the barn and the year the last square dance was held.

properties.Name: Southminster Church
properties.ShortDescription: Southminster Evangelical United Brethren Church is a well-preserved example of a late gothic revival style church built just after World War II. The simple design, by notable architect Fritz Craig, relies on the stone exterior, stained glass windows, and interior wood trusses to elevate the building. Last, this is the best remaining representation of the congregations—Caldwell Memorial and Calvary Chapel—which merged to become Southminster.
